<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RVs Increasing on America's Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANASSAS, Va. (AP) -- In an age of conspicuous consumption,  
nothing says rest and relaxation like a behemoth RV. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to a roaring economy, baby boomers with money to spend  
and Americans' love affair with sport utility vehicles, more people 
are buying RVs, those lumbering vacation homes on wheels. 
</P>
<P>
	More Americans than ever own RVs in terms of sheer numbers and  
as a percentage of the population. There are 9.3 million on the 
road, accounting for nearly 10 percent of all vehicle-owning 
households in the United States, according to the Recreation 
Vehicle Industry Association, based in Reston. 
</P>
<P>
	Depending on who's talking, the RV boom signals a shift in  
Americans' ideals, shows their longing for community or indicates a 
growing desire to escape to the wilderness. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's no question that, as with luxury boats, RV sales are  
a good indicator of the economy's performance, said David 
Humphreys, president of the RV association. ``If the economy is 
doing well, we're doing well,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And RVs, sometimes seen as a vehicle for seniors, are being  
bought by younger people than in the past. RV-owning boomers with 
families now outnumber the traditional core market of over-55 empty 
nesters, with the average age of RV owners at 48, according to the 
RV association. 
</P>
<P>
	Ownership among 45- to 54-year-olds has grown by 25 percent  
since 1993 -- more than any other age bracket, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill and Gayle Putt of Warrenton are among the Americans who  
have joined the RV culture in recent years. They strolled the 
showroom at Reines RV Center in Manassas recently, looking for 
something more spacious than their present 29-foot motor home. 
</P>
<P>
	The Putts -- he's 48 and she's 42 -- said that with three children  
and a dog, an RV allows the family to get away at a moment's notice 
on weekend trips, such as recent expeditions to Chesapeake Bay and 
North Carolina's Outer Banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have the ability to go anywhere,'' Mrs. Putt said. ``It's  
great family time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Small, towable units cost as little as $3,300, while the largest  
motor homes can cost more than $300,000 and offer basement storage, 
washers and dryers, satellite dishes, VCRs and even hot tubs. Some 
have walls that, with the touch of a button, expand out several 
feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the 1970s and early 1980s, motor homes were generally  
looked down on, said Gerald Celente, head of the Trends Research 
Institute in Rhinebeck, N.Y., and author of Trends 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were for middle-America, retired blue-collar workers,''  
he said. ``After you did your time on the assembly line, heaven was 
driving around in your portable home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with sport utility vehicles crowding the roads, it's cool  
to own a gas guzzler, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Americans' love for SUVs means there are more vehicles on the  
roads that can tow non-motorized RVs, said Lindsey Reines, owner of 
Reines RV Center. Reines is so confident about his booming sales 
that he's expanded the size of his dealership. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's roughly 8,000 commercial RV parks are also  
capitalizing on the trends by expanding and teaming with 
manufacturers to pitch RVs as a way of life. Some of these parks 
have become mini resorts with water slides, theme parks, organized 
day trips and shuttle buses to nearby attractions, said David 
Gorin, president of the National Association of RV Parks &AMP; 
Campgrounds in Falls Church. 
</P>
<P>
	A park near Gettysburg, Pa., is one of a handful that has Civil  
War-themed activities such as battlefield visits. Others have 
linked up with golf courses, and a campground in Ocean City, Md., 
called Frontier City has built an amusement park with a Wild West 
flavor. 
</P>
<P>
	In Florida, Arizona and other winter roosts for seniors, RV  
parks are marketing themselves as a cheaper alternative to a 
vacation home. 
</P>
<P>
	RV parks also cater to city lovers. Cherry Hill Park in College  
Park, Md., is just off the Washington Beltway and has its own Metro 
stop with trains that connect it to the capital. Aquia Pines in 
Stafford, Va., runs buses into Washington, Gorin said. 
</P>
<P>
	For those who dislike RVs, hold on for a long ride.  
</P>
<P>
	``As the baby boomers age, the roads are going to be flooded  
with these things,'' Celente said. ``It's no longer looked upon as 
unhip to hog the road.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
