<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves Put Smoltz on Disabled List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Braves right-hander John Smoltz was put back on  
the 15-day disabled list Monday night with a strained right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz (8-3), who had surgery on the elbow in the winter of 1998  
and was on the DL twice last season despite a 17-3 record, also 
went on the DL on May 15 and came back June 1, going 3-2 with two 
no-decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz gave up 10 hits and seven runs in 6 1-3 innings in  
Sunday's loss to the Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's inflammation there and it needs rest,'' Smoltz said.  
``Hopefully it'll calm down and I'll be able to resume pitching 
soon. I'm not going to pick up a ball for 10 days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie left-hander Bruce Chen, who was 0-0 with a 4.50 ERA in  
two previous starts with Atlanta when Smoltz went on the DL earlier 
in the season, was recalled from Triple-A Richmond where he was 6-3 
with a 3.87 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz did not set a timetable for his return.  
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be able to pitch by the end of the year. That's my  
main goal,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves also found out after Monday's 6-5 win over Florida  
that the injury to catcher Javy Lopez's right knee may be more 
serious than originally believed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lopez, who strained his right knee while sliding into second  
base on an attempted steal on June 20 at Arizona, was placed on the 
15-day DL and is eligible to be activated Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lopez, hitting .321 with 11 home runs and 37 RBIs in 56 games,  
took batting practice for the first time since the injury on Monday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling pretty good. I can hit, but I can't squat,'' said  
Lopez, who was wearing a brace that ran from his thigh to his 
ankle, making it virtually impossible for him to catch. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if he would be out for the rest of the season, Lopez  
replied: ``I can't answer that question.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He indicated that he might have a partial tear of a ligament in  
his knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Braves orthopedic surgeon Dr. Joe Chandler, however, would not  
confirm that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're treating the injury conservatively with rest and  
rehabilitation,'' he said. ``Hopefully, he'll be back in 1-2 
weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eddie Perez has caught every game since Lopez was injured.  
Rookie catcher Pascual Matos was recalled from Triple-A Richmond on 
June 23, but has played sparingly, going hitless in three at-bats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
