<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Up; Gold Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading Monday. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0224, down from $1.0240 Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Friday: 122.26 Japanese  
yen, up from 120.96; 1.5692 Swiss francs, up from 1.5665; and 
1.4628 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4666 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5746, down from $1.5778.  
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets were closed in the United States for the  
Independence Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.9130 German marks, up from 1.9100; 
6.4159 French francs, up from 6.4058; 2.1554 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.1521; and 1,893.85 Italian lire, up from 1,890.89. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $261.90 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$263.20 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $261.85, down from $262.95.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell 50 cents in Hong Kong to $262.85.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.25 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.28. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
