<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Gains Half-Berth in World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The third-place team in Asian qualifying will  
play a team from Europe for the final berth in the 2002 World Cup, 
averting a threatened boycott by the Asians, a member of FIFA's 
executive committee said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	With Japan and South Korea qualifying automatically as co-hosts,  
just two teams were set to advance from the Asian qualifying 
tournament. Those two nations and Saudi Arabia qualified for last 
year's tournament in France along with Iran, which won a playoff 
with Australia for the final spot. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, FIFA decided Europe would get 15 spots in the  
32-nation field, including defending champion France. If the change 
gains approved, which is expected at Tuesday's FIFA executive 
committee meeting, the 14th team in Europe qualifying must play the 
third-place team in Asia qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	South America gets four spots, and its fifth-place team will  
play the Oceania champion for another spot. 
</P>
<P>
	North and Central America and the Caribbean gets three spots and  
Africa five. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 10:10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newsmagazines Take On Different Look </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A ship heads out to some Atlantic Ocean fishing  
spots and never returns. A disabled man tries to climb Mount 
Everest. A scientist descends into the belly of an active volcano 
for research. 
</P>
<P>
	They sound like the pitches for some promising movies. Instead,  
these story lines feature in the summer's entertaining new crop of 
TV newsmagazines. 
</P>
<P>
	Adventure! Mystery! Suspense!  
</P>
<P>
	Serious network journalists never used to worry about Hollywood  
storytelling devices. But the summer network schedule suggests 
times have changed. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC News is producing a six-week replacement series,  
``Vanished,'' that features true tales of people who disappeared: 
the crew of the Atlantic fishing vessel profiled in the 
best-seller, ``The Perfect Storm''; and a man who twice walked away 
from his life and all who knew him. 
</P>
<P>
	At CBS, the newsmagazine ``48 Hours'' added ``48 Hours Monday  
Mysteries'' that plumbs unresolved true stories, many of them 
updates of previous features on network news programs. 
</P>
<P>
	It has done so well in the ratings that CBS begins ``48 Hours  
Tuesday Adventures'' starting tomorrow. The show will revisit 
stories like the mountain climber with one leg and a New Yorker who 
travels to Spain each year for the running of the bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	Both shows are at 10 p.m. EDT.  
</P>
<P>
	Newsmagazines are particularly important to networks in the  
summer. Their ratings tend to go up, or at least not shrink as much 
as the reruns of comedies and dramas. Since they're cheap to 
produce, Hollywood executives are increasingly calling news 
divisions to plug holes in the prime-time schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``The West Coast sees that the audience loves reality  
programming,'' said Susan Zirinsky, executive producer of ``48 
Hours.'' ``It's a good way for the news division to fill a need. 
It's the best of both worlds. We love to do it and they like the 
product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With ``Dateline NBC'' on five times a week and ``20/20'' four,  
newsmagazines must do something to distinguish themselves, said 
Russ Ptacek, publisher of NewsTV Report, a newsletter that monitors 
the content of these shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes just plain ``48 Hours'' won't do.  
</P>
<P>
	``Vanished'' is something of an experiment, as ABC News tries to  
apply to non-fiction the same storytelling techniques viewers are 
familiar with from dramas or magazines, said Phyllis McGrady, the 
network executive in charge of the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time, documentaries weren't keeping up with the  
pace of what viewers like to see in other mediums,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each ``Vanished'' is an original show. While the ``48 Hours''  
editions are based on reruns, each contains new footage that 
updates the story. 
</P>
<P>
	The danger for these organizations is in letting entertainment  
values override news judgment. Are any reputations being 
compromised by making shows that appeal to Hollywood? 
</P>
<P>
	``I consider these to be entertaining, but I don't consider them  
to be entertainment,'' McGrady said. ``On the other hand, I watched 
`The Practice' the other night and it almost seemed like news. 
There's an interesting blurring of the lines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CBS's Zirinsky said that between her, ``60 Minutes'' executive  
producer Don Hewitt and ``60 Minutes II'' executive producer Jeff 
Fager, ``you couldn't get any more old school. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing that we do that's compromised,'' she said.  
``And I don't say that lightly, because it's something that we talk 
about all the time. I'm always worried that we're considered the 
stodgy ones. I don't think this hurts us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The success of the special editions bolsters her independence,  
Zirinsky said. ``We don't feel the pressures of entertainment to do 
certain kinds of stories,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The extra hours on the air convey another benefit, giving ``48  
Hours'' a greater ``quick strike'' capability to tackle breaking 
news subjects in prime time, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	That responsiveness is something that ``Dateline NBC'' prides  
itself on. ``Dateline'' isn't attempting any repackaging of its own 
for the summer. Its only new wrinkle is to devote Friday nights to 
hour-long documentaries on weighty topics like welfare reform and 
gambling addiction, said Neal Shapiro, executive producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Shapiro doesn't see anything wrong with telling compelling  
stories in dramatic fashion. Ptacek also doesn't mind the breezy 
new summer style. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the product is being diluted,'' he said, ``so  
much as the product is offering additional flavors.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	ROCK AND ROLL: Comedian Chris Rock has agreed to be host of the  
16th annual MTV Video Music Awards, airing live from the 
Metropolitan Opera House in New York City on Sept. 9. Rock was a 
hit anchoring the show two years ago. Rock's HBO special, ``Bigger 
and Blacker,'' debuts on July 10, and his HBO series begins its 
fourth season Sept. 17. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	David Bauder can be reached at dbauder''at''ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
