<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific Has Most ATMs in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The Asia-Pacific region has the most automated  
teller machines in the world, a news report said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asia-Pacific had 275,007 ATMs as of 1998, 34.4 percent of  
the world's total, The Straits Times newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Western Europe was second with 218,394, or 27.2 percent, the  
newspaper said, while North America was third with 214,832, or 26.8 
percent. The paper quoted statistics from Retail Banking Research 
in Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan had the world's highest concentration of ATMs, with  
1,079.7 per million people in 1997, the most recent year for which 
density statistics were given. South Korea was second at 791 per 
million, and Spain was third with 761.4 per million. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of ATMs worldwide grew by 14 percent to some 802,000  
in 1998, the report said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
