<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shooter Strikes City on Big Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- A delegation of Taiwanese officials  
came to their sister city looking forward to a weekend of picnics 
and Fourth of July fireworks displays. 
</P>
<P>
	They also saw Bloomington on one of its darkest days.  
</P>
<P>
	The group from Lu Jou, Taiwan, was in the college town Sunday,  
the same day a Korean graduate student was shot twice in the back 
and killed outside a church by a white supremacist. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday really sent a shock wave through our community,''  
said Bloomington Mayor John Fernandez, on the verge of tears Monday 
morning. ``It broke up what should have been a celebratory day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Sunday's shooting, police escorted the delegation to a  
picnic and fireworks display. Fernandez spent most of Monday 
entertaining the five-member delegation, trying to make them feel 
at ease. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloomington and Lu Jou have been sister cities for 10 years, but  
this was the first time Mayor Chein-Hui ``David'' Huang had visited 
Bloomington, a city 60 miles southwest of Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, in town for a cultural and educational exchange, said the  
killing did nothing to affect his opinion of Bloomington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bloomington is a peaceful city,'' he said. ``All the people  
here were very kind. The city is beautiful.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
