<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Launches Currency Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) -- Bulgaria lopped three zeroes off its  
currency on Monday and introduced new bills in a reform aimed at 
simplifying accounting and transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Monday, 1.9098 leva bought one U.S. dollar.  
</P>
<P>
	Under a currency board Bulgaria enacted in its central bank two  
years ago, the lev was pegged at 1,000 to the German mark and later 
at 1,955.83 to the euro. Now those exchange rates move to one lev 
for one German mark and 1.95583 leva per euro. 
</P>
<P>
	The reform doesn't change the purchasing power of the lev, as  
prices were adjusted accordingly. 
</P>
<P>
	New 1, 2, 5, 20 and 50 leva bills are replacing the previous  
100, 200, 500, 1,000, 2,000, 5,000, 10,000 and 50,000 leva bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the new and old currencies will circulate until the end of  
the year. After that, the central bank will take the old leva out 
of circulation but continue to exchange them for new ones. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
