<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Holiday Heat Wilts the East  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Record heat and sticky, humid air enveloped the  
eastern third of the nation today, wilting people outdoors and 
pushing air conditioners into overdrive. The National Weather 
Service posted heat advisories from the Mississippi Valley to the 
East Coast. It warned that high temperatures and humidity would 
create heat indexes of up to 110 and more. In Newark, N.J., the 
temperature reached a record 102 degrees. New York City hit a 
record 100 and Philadelphia tied its record at 100. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Going to Poor U.S. Sites  
</P>
<P>
	HAZARD, Ky. (AP) -- President Clinton today began a four-day tour  
of some of America's poorest spots, bringing a message of hope for 
the needy and of opportunity for corporate America. With 
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman and Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton, 
Clinton launched his visits. About 2,000 people waving tiny 
American flags waited hours in blazing heat to glimpse the 
president at Hazard, Ky. His trip to six states is designed to 
highlight legislation that would help leverage corporate investment 
in impoverished areas 

</P>
<P>
	NATO-Russia Deal Is Reached  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Russia and NATO reached an agreement  
today opening the way for Moscow to deploy more troops into Kosovo. 
NATO hopes the deployment of Russian forces will reassure Kosovo 
Serbs, who feel their fellow Slavs and traditional allies will 
protect them better than Western troops. Flights of Russian troops 
into Kosovo could begin as soon as tomorrow. The head of the U.N. 
refugee agency, on a visit to Kosovo, said she feared for the 
safety of Serbs and Gypsies as ethnic Albanians return home after 
being brutally driven out by Yugoslav forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Barak Speak by Telephone  
</P>
<P>
	HAZARD, Ky. (AP) -- President Clinton spoke briefly today with  
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak. Barak, scheduled to take 
office this week, is expected to visit Washington within a few 
weeks. The two leaders discussed the possibility of a visit, though 
no date was set. Barak has named his Cabinet and promised to bring 
the country peace and prosperity. 

</P>
<P>
	15 Workers Injured in La. Blasts  
</P>
<P>
	GRAMERCY, La. (AP) -- A series of explosions heard for miles  
shook an aluminum plant early today, injuring at least 15 workers 
and spraying a caustic chemical over the area. Authorities told 
residents to stay indoors and close their windows. No one was 
killed in the blast at the Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical Co. plant, 
said a state police officer. The explosions at about 5:15 a.m. 
occurred in an area where electricity is generated and where 
bauxite, a reddish and clay-like aluminum ore, is mixed with a 
liquid form of sodium hydroxide, a caustic chemical. 

</P>
<P>
	Ill. Slay Suspect Killed Self  
</P>
<P>
	SALEM, Ill. (AP) -- A white supremacist who targeted minorities  
in a shooting spree that killed two and injured several in two 
states fatally shot himself after grappling with police, 
investigators said. Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 21, was being pursued 
Sunday after he carjacked a van in rural Marion County, Ill., said 
the FBI. Authorities believe Smith began his drive-by killing spree 
in Chicago on Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Backs Faster Internet Link  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The U.N.'s telecommunications agency today pushed  
for a global agreement on a new telephone standard, saying it will 
vastly speed up links from homes to the Internet. U.S. firms are 
already offering the new standard, which enables speeds at least 30 
times faster than the current top-of-the-line modems over ordinary 
telephone lines. The new standard is for ASDL, or Asymmetric 
Digital Subscriber Line. 

</P>
<P>
	'Wild Wild West' Tops Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Will Smith's ``Wild Wild West'' roped about  
$36.8 million in movie ticket sales over the Fourth of July holiday 
weekend. ``Big Daddy'' with Adam Sandler came in second at the 
weekend box office, while ``Tarzan'' was third. 

</P>
<P>
	World Stocks Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher today, with oil,  
telecommunications and chemical companies leading the way. In Japan 
and Hong Kong, the main stock gauges rose to their highest levels 
in more than 20 months. Other markets in Asia closed generally 
higher. 

</P>
<P>
	Reds Defeat Astros  
</P>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- The Cincinnati Reds today regained sole  
possession of first place in the NL Central, beating the Houston 
Astros 5-2 in sweltering heat. For the Reds, Ron Villone (4-2) got 
the win, but his streak of 21 scoreless innings -- second-longest in 
the majors this season -- was snapped by Matt Mieske's two-run 
homer. Cincinnati's Aaron Boone had three hits for the second 
straight game and Mike Cameron homered. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
</P>
