<HEADLINE> Pyrotechnic Blowups Kill Four People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Holiday weekend fireworks accidents killed four people as  
pyrotechnics displays misfired or blew up prematurely in two towns. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the victims were fatally injured in Centerville, Ark.,  
when one fireworks shell exploded just after it was launched 
Sunday, shooting a fireball into the open door of a trailer where 
more fireworks were being assembled. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a dud that went about treetop high and then went  
off,'' said witness Roy Tillman. ``Then the whole thing blew up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion took place about a quarter-mile from spectators.  
</P>
<P>
	Two teen-agers were killed in the blast, and a 32-year-old man  
died Monday at a Little Rock hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Walls, a supervisor at Henderson Specialties, the company  
that put on the show, said the youths who died were relatives of 
the company's owner. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took as many precautions as we could,'' Walls said.  
</P>
<P>
	In Peoria, Ariz., stacks of fireworks started detonating Sunday  
while workers from the Salt Lake City-based Lantis Fireworks were 
still unloading them for a Fourth of July show there, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	One worker suffered burns over 90 percent of her body and died  
Monday. Four others were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The blasts shook windows a half-mile away.  
</P>
<P>
	``There must've been 50 to 60 explosions,'' said Chris Powell,  
who was setting up his camera across the street to photograph the 
display. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, officials in Gardendale, Ala., were investigating  
whether fireworks caused a house fire that left five family members 
dead Monday. The family, including three children ages 6 to 10, had 
apparently shot off fireworks in their yard late Sunday, Deputy 
Fire Chief Robert Ryant said. 
</P>
<P>
	The blaze appeared to have started in garbage cans outside the  
house, then spread to the dining room and filled the house with 
smoke, Ryant said. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, seven people suffered minor injuries in a fireworks  
mishap at West Bend, Wis.; a 13-year-old boy was in critical 
condition Monday after being struck in the face by fireworks in 
Washington's Snohomish County; and a teen-ager lost the tips of his 
fingers to a large firecracker at Martha Lake, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	In Dilworth, Minn., 20-year-old Terry Engel lost his right index  
finger when a cherry bomb exploded in his hand. He also was charged 
with disorderly conduct because police believe he intended to toss 
the device into a squad car. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
