<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Commission Explains UBS Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERN, Switzerland (AP) -- Staff and organizational shortcomings  
at one of the banks which merged to create Switzerland's UBS AG 
were behind its huge loss following exposure to a troubled U.S. 
investment fund, the Swiss Federal Banking Commission said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	UBS, Europe's biggest bank, was formed last year from the merger  
of Swiss Bank Corp. and Union Bank of Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, UBS reported a net third-quarter loss of 911  
million Swiss francs (then worth about $660 million), largely due 
to its exposure to the private Long Term Capital Management hedge 
fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Failings at Union Bank of Switzerland caused the loss, which  
resulted in the resignation last October of UBS chairman Mathis 
Cabiallavetta and the departure of three other top executives, the 
Swiss commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the panel said its investigation of the debacle concluded  
that the new bank's organization is adequate for an international 
financial institution of its size. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizational weaknesses have now been largely eliminated, it  
added, noting those involved with the fund loss are no longer with 
the bank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
