<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Olympians Close Out Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Thousands of Special Olympics athletes  
observed a moment of silence during closing ceremonies for the 10th 
World Summer Games -- an event marred by three deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	During the nine-day international competition that ended Sunday  
a 14-year-old athlete died in his sleep, a volunteer collapsed and 
died minutes after opening ceremonies, and University of North 
Carolina chancellor Michael Hooker died of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Hooker, 53, was on the Special Olympics board of directors and  
played a key part in bringing the games to the area. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, two Dominican basketball players and two Moroccan  
soccer players slipped away from their delegations in the event's 
opening days. Three of them have been heard from since, but one of 
the Moroccans remains unaccounted-for, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the moment of silence, Tim Shriver, head of Special  
Olympics Inc., urged the 7,000 participants gathered at the closing 
ceremony Sunday to look with optimism toward the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the 21st century, our athletes will not only compete but  
lead,'' Shriver said. ``I want everyone to go away from here 
thinking: 'Label me able not disabled.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1963 by Eunice Kennedy Shriver, the event this year  
featured competitors with mental retardation from 150 countries. 
There were about 2,000 coaches, 15,000 friends and relatives and 
45,000 volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to believe the Shrivers, who have seen it for 30 years,  
that this was the best ever,'' said LeRoy Walker, president of the 
Games and former president of the United States Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The next world Special Olympics competition, the Winter Games,  
will be held in 2001 in Alaska. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
