<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Wild Wild West' Tops Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Wild Wild West'' won the box office money  
shootout over the Fourth of July weekend, beating a posse of strong 
challengers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Will Smith Western with sci-fi overtones triumphed over bad  
reviews to take in $36.8 million on its opening weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Big Daddy'' with Adam Sandler dropped to second place but  
still earned $26.4 million over the four-day holiday weekend. 
``Tarzan'' was third with $19.2 million, according to industry 
estimates released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``South Park'' feature opened to a respectable $14.8 million  
despite new tougher enforcement of the R rating, which limited the 
audience. Spike Lee's latest film, ``Summer of Sam,'' was in eighth 
place with a lackluster $7.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the box office handle was up 16 percent from the 1998  
Independence Day weekend, which had ``Armageddon'' as the big 
opener, easily keeping the year on a record pace, said Paul 
Dergarabedian, president of box office tracker Exhibitor Relations 
Co. Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we've ever seen such a competitive marketplace  
and at the same time seen such an expansion of the audience,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wild Wild West'' had an impressive $11,011-per-screen average  
in 3,342 theaters. The loose remake of the TV series has collected 
$50.1 million since opening last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the film was far from Smith's biggest July Fourth opener.  
Both ``Men in Black'' ($51 million) and ``Independence Day'' ($50 
million) had stronger first-weekend openings. 
</P>
<P>
	``West'' also trailed ``Armageddon's'' three-day debut total of  
$36 million last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The monstrous weekend was powered, instead, by the strength of  
the holdovers: ``Big Daddy'' dropped 36 percent from the previous 
weekend -- a modest decline considering its stunning $41.5 million 
debut -- and ``Tarzan'' slipped only 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The General's Daughter'' hung onto fifth place with a tiny 4  
percent drop to $14.6 million, while ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The 
Phantom Menace'' earned another $11.7 million after a 17 percent 
drop. 
</P>
<P>
	Only ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' appeared to be  
losing its mojo, tumbling 41 percent in the fourth week to $10.8 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the few disappointments was the critically mixed ``Summer  
of Sam,'' the tale of a hot summer in New York when serial killer 
David Berkowitz ran amok. The film's Friday-through-Sunday take of 
$6 million was below that of Lee's other works: ``Jungle Fever'' (a 
three-day opening of $13 million in 1991) and ``Malcolm X'' ($9.9 
million in 1992.) 
</P>
<P>
	``Summer of Sam'' was another summer setback for Disney's  
live-action film division. While the animated ``Tarzan'' flew high, 
``Instinct'' -- with Anthony Hopkins and Cuba Gooding Jr. -- dropped 
out of the Top 10 with $785,000 for 12th. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated grosses for Friday through Monday at North American  
theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co.: 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``Wild Wild West,'' $36.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Big Daddy,'' $26.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``Tarzan,'' $19.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' $14.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``The General's Daughter,'' $14.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' $11.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' $10.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``Summer of Sam,'' $7.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``Notting Hill,'' $5.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``An Ideal Husband,'' $3.4 million.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
