<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Mineral Water Is Called OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A Dutch laboratory said Monday that  
bacteria found in samples of a mineral water bottled by Coca-Cola 
in Poland was not hazardous. 
</P>
<P>
	The TNO Nutrition and Food Research Institute in The Netherlands  
identified the bacteria detected by Polish health officials as 
coliform, according to a TNO statement distributed by Coca-Cola. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola recalled an estimated 180,000 half-liter (about 16  
ounce) plastic bottles of Bonaqa Plus brand mineral water on Friday 
after the bacteria showed up in testing. No illness was reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Polish authorities had said the bacteria belonged to a broad  
group that rarely is toxic. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall of the Bonaqa Plus mineral water, a new product  
fortified with calcium and magnesium, extended a problematic summer 
for Coca-Cola in Europe. More than 200 people complained of illness 
last month from drinking Coca-Cola beverages in Belgium and France, 
leading to a costly recall of the company's products in those 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the discovery on June 25 by a Polish consumer of mold  
in a bottle of mineral water, which caused the company last week to 
withdraw all of its beverages in 0.33 liter (about 12 ounce) 
returnable glass bottles. 
</P>
<P>
	A further recall of the bacteria-contaminated Bonaqa Plus  
plastic bottles followed on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola said the mold and bacteria were not hazardous but that  
it recalled its beverages to maintain public trust in its products. 
It said returnable bottles would be washed better. 
</P>
<P>
	Production was shut down at its bottling plant in southwest  
Poland to check for the source of the bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Storeowners said last week Coca-Cola products continued to sell  
normally, and consumers said they would continue to drink the 
company's beverages. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
