<HEADLINE> Politics 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Gary Bauer  
said Monday that Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for 
the GOP nomination, has a responsibility to take a stand against 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said Bush could influence Congress' pending vote on  
extending normal trade relations with China by coming out against 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should not be rewarding China again with the thing they  
want most from us,'' Bauer said while campaigning in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said that by giving China normal trade relations --  
formerly called most-favored-nation status -- the United States 
surrenders the greatest leverage it has to end human rights abuses 
in China. 
</P>
<P>
	As the apparent leader of the pack of Republican presidential  
contenders, Bush should take the ``moral stand,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush has sharply criticized the Clinton administration for  
not acting sooner to stop China from stealing U.S. nuclear secrets, 
he has said he believes Chinese society will benefit from trade 
with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush knows China is a competitor, but he feels it's  
important for China's markets to be open to U.S. producers and 
products,'' his spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker, said Monday. ``It's 
important for people to remember that when we export goods, we also 
export freedom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House's trade policy committee gave its support Thursday to  
President Clinton's decision to extend normal relations with China 
for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CHARLES CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Many of the problems facing American  
families today can be traced to television, former Vice President 
Dan Quayle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The average teen-ager spends 1,500 hours a year watching TV,  
600 hours a year in school and 30 hours a year talking to their 
parents. I ask you, who's in control?'' Quayle asked Monday at a 
holiday picnic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Family is the number one priority, the number one issue as we  
go into the next century,'' the Republican presidential nomination 
hopeful said. ``The way to strengthen the family is to bring back 
good common sense and strong moral values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEREDITH, N.H. (AP) -- Sen. Bob Smith is hoping a wave of support  
from the nation's roughly 30 million veterans could sweep him 
toward the GOP presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	But that route could be crowded. That territory already has been  
staked out by Arizona Sen. John McCain, a prisoner of war for more 
than five years in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, a New Hampshire Republican, met with a handful of  
veterans at a prisoners of war memorial on the shore of Lake 
Winnepesauke on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He proposed spending some of $18 billion in federal money  
earmarked for the United Nations, International Monetary Fund and 
other international organizations to help veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to make an appeal to the 27 or 30 million veterans,''  
Smith said. ``I will take that $18 billion and use it to get 
homeless veterans off the grates. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I'm president, if I have to, we'll put them in the White  
House.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said that if veterans endorse him, it will give him a  
strong stance in the race for the Republican nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping Senator Smith at least puts these issues on the  
front burner,'' said Vietnam veteran Bob Jones, 53, of Meredith. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was a vice chairman of a Senate committee created in 1992  
to examine the fate of soldiers missing in action in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	While Smith's proposal to help veterans was well received  
Monday, his talk about leaving the Republican party to run as a 
third-party candidate was not. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you leave the Republican party, I really feel you should  
step down from the Senate,'' said Vietnam veteran Mike Hatch, 57, 
of Meredith. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he will decide within three weeks whether to form a  
third party. He said too many Republicans -- including Texas Gov. 
George Bush, the GOP presidential front-runner -- have gone soft on 
issues like abortion and gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WOLFEBORO, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Pat  
Buchanan is dismissing Sen. Bob Smith's talk of making a 
third-party bid for the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative commentator said Monday he'd rather see GOP  
candidates unite conservatives within ``a fighting second party -- 
the Republican party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, R-N.H., has said he will decide by August whether to  
continue his presidential campaign as a Republican, or break away 
and start a new, more conservative party. 
</P>
<P>
	While campaigning in New Hampshire on Monday, Buchanan also said  
that while he and Smith are competing for the same conservative 
votes, only he has proven he can win. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan won the New Hampshire primary in 1996.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can win and I have won,'' Buchanan said. He said winning a  
straw poll of conservative voters in Hopkinton on Sunday convinced 
him he can repeat his 1996 performance. 
  	   	
</P>
