<DOCNO> APW19990705.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 18:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Mariners Ballpark Dedicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The hot dogs are tastier, the seats more  
comfortable, the views much better and the open air glorious, 
Seattle Mariners fans said Monday at the dedication of their new 
ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	So what if service at the concession stands was slow and the  
relish table ill-designed? 
</P>
<P>
	A day after Ken Griffey Jr. weighed in on the side of public  
officials in a dispute over financing, a crowd estimated at 15,000 
cheered the impending return of outdoor baseball after more than 
two decades in the Kingdome. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of who should pay for $100 million in cost overruns  
on the $517 million project seemed almost lost in the shadows. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care, just as long as they play ball here,'' said Rob  
Eason of Spanaway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're back to the way baseball ought to be played --  
outdoors, on the grass,'' Orlin VanWieringen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners could hardly have ordered more perfect weather for  
the festivities, a cloudless sky with a light breeze and 
temperatures edging into the 70s -- the warmest, sunniest weather in 
more than three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``For too long we have suffered with less than the best. Today  
we have the best,'' Mayor Paul Schell said. ``It's time to 
celebrate a great stadium that all of our children and our 
children's children can enjoy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute was evident only in the lackluster applause and a  
few boos for club president Chuck Armstrong, who ignored the snub 
and proclaimed, ``What a great day out for baseball! Ain't baseball 
great?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong was a last-minute stand-in for Mariners chairman John  
Ellis, who has borne most of the load in the club's demand for $60 
million in additional public funding. 
</P>
<P>
	An article Sunday in The Seattle Times said Ellis and others  
suggested the Mariners might trade Griffey or Alex Rodriguez if the 
demand was rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time this team has something come up, it's always me and  
Alex to blame,'' Griffey told ESPN on Sunday. ``We love the game. 
We love playing in front of 40,000, 50,000 fans at home. Why does 
John Ellis want to make it so hard for us to bring those people 
out? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not us asking for more money here. I've been here 11  
years, Jay Buhner has been here 11 years. How much money do we have 
to defer? I deferred $5 million in my salary and offered to defer 
$10 million. They turned it down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team was in Anaheim to play the Angels on Monday night, so  
the players missed the dedication. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
