<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Posada Apologizes to Umpires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Yankees catcher Jorge Posada apologized  
in person Monday for calling umpires out of shape, telling Greg 
Kosc's crew he made a mistake by popping off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said something I shouldn't have said,'' Posada said. ``There  
was a lot of frustration built up. I'm going to tell the guy I'm 
sorry. Hopefully, he's here today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Kosc, the main target after leaving Sunday's game because of  
heat exhaustion, was not present when Posada visited the umpires' 
locker room before the Yankees played Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosc went home for further tests, a day after being hospitalized  
on an extremely humid afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Crew chief Larry Barnett said Kosc would probably be out for a  
few days. Bill Miller, a regular ump in the Triple-A Pacific Coast 
League, took Kosc's place. 
</P>
<P>
	After talking to Posada, Barnett said the whole matter was ``a  
dead issue.'' The weight of umpires, however, remains a delicate 
topic in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought a lot about it all day, thinking of cute things to  
say,'' Barnett said. ``But I think the best thing for me to do is 
just to say that it's a shame you have to go through things like 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've done some dumb things in my life,'' said Barnett,  
retiring after this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Posada was not in the starting lineup Monday night. During the  
day, temperatures in New York hit a record 100 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the weather got to everybody yesterday,'' Yankees  
manager Joe Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	Posada, who said he took water to Kosc during Sunday's game, was  
called out on strikes by the plate umpire in a 7-3 loss. Later, he 
struck back. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is the guys are not in shape,'' Posada said.  
``I understand it's hot, but you have to be able to go through the 
whole game. They're not prepared, they're not in shape. It's a 
shame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kosc, 50, is a 24-year AL veteran. He's listed at 255 pounds and  
one of his hobbies is weightlifting. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he (Posada) ever got a chance to go through a workout with  
Greg, he'd see that Greg was a man,'' Barnett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees general manager Brian Cashman talked to Posada on Monday  
about his comments. 
</P>
<P>
	``He woke up this morning and realized he'd said some things in  
the heat of battle,'' Cashman said. ``Jorge said he was going to 
apologize and I was glad to hear that. It's important that a person 
can stand up and own up to a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Posada admitted to being steamed and bothered the previous day.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was hot. We lost. I got a pitch called on me that wasn't a  
strike,'' Posada said. ``But I was wrong to say what I did. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's just leave it at that and not make it a big deal,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	NL umpire Eric Gregg, who has repeatedly battled weight  
troubles, has been on leave for more than a month. 
</P>
<P>
	NL umpire John McSherry, who weighed more than 325 pounds, died  
of a heart attack on the field at Cincinnati on opening day in 
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
