<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A leftist guerrilla group has yet to  
punish a squad leader it blames for the slayings of three American 
Indian rights activists in March, a top rebel commander said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorge Briceno, the No. 2 leader of the Revolutionary Armed  
Forces of Colombia, or FARC, refuted media reports that the guilty 
rebel officer had been punished, in an interview published in El 
Espectador newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The FARC claims a rogue local squad leader carried out the  
slayings of three Americans whose bodies were found March 4 just 
across the border in Venezuela, a week after they were abducted 
while working with a Colombian Indian tribe, the U'wa. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the killings, the Clinton Administration severed all  
contacts with the guerrilla group and is demanding it hand over the 
killers to Colombian, Venezuelan or U.S. authorities. The FARC has 
refused to do so, vowing instead to apply its own system of 
``revolutionary justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many here suspect a low-ranking rebel will take the fall in the  
killing of the Americans for higher-ups in the 15,000-member rebel 
group who allegedly issued the orders. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori is so secretive  
about whether he will run for a third consecutive term in office 
next year that not even his children know his plans, his daughter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keiko Sofia Fujimori, the president's eldest daughter and acting  
First Lady, said in a interview published Monday in the Lima 
newspaper La Republica that she hoped her father didn't run again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my father to find a wife and spend more time with his  
children,'' said Keiko Sofia, 24, who recently graduated with a 
business degree from Boston University. 
</P>
<P>
	Fujimori, the son of Japanese immigrants, was first elected in  
1990 as a political outsider and re-elected in a landslide in 1995, 
but his popularity has wavered in his second term. 
</P>
<P>
	Fujimori's 22-year marriage to Susana Higuchi ended in a bitter  
divorce in 1996. The couple have four children. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican police found the bodies of four  
suspected members of a drug cartel along a highway near the U.S. 
border, the government news agency Notimex reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies, blindfolded and cuffed, were inside an abandoned  
luxury car near the hamlet of Lucio Blanco, 20 miles south of 
Brownsville, Texas, Notimex said, quoting police. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators believe the victims were gunmen for a former head  
of the Gulf drug cartel, and the gangland-style killing suggests it 
was carried out by other drug dealers, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez already had his  
own radio and TV shows. Now he is adding a new tool to his small 
state-run media empire: a newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``The President's Mail'' hit newsstands on Monday with 32 pages  
of news articles, editorials and opinion columns that Chavez says 
will serve as an alternative to the mainstream media, which he 
charges is biased in favor of the country's corrupt political 
elite. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez is listed as the newspaper's editor-in-chief.  
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the paper, along with the weekly call-in radio and  
TV shows that Chavez hosts on state-run channels, is part of the 
president's alleged plan to impose dictatorial rule by controlling 
key institutions and eliminating opposition voices. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
