<DOCNO> APW19990705.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 04:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jarrett Builds Winston Cup Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Dale Jarrett experienced the quickest  
four seconds in auto racing over the weekend. Next, he tries to 
survive the longest five months of his life. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to a four-second `gas-and-go'' pit stop towards the end  
of the Pepsi 400 on Saturday, Jarrett took a lead, then held off 
several challenges, including a late run from Dale Earnhardt, to 
win the race. 
</P>
<P>
	It expanded Jarrett's lead in the Winston Cup points standings  
to 177 points over Bobby Labonte, a huge cushion as the drivers 
head into the second half of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1993, no driver with the points lead after the Pepsi 400  
has failed to win the title. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a good stat to know,'' said Jarrett, in pursuit of his  
first series title. ``I don't want to end that string. Without 
sounding cocky or overconfident, if we can continue doing what 
we've done, they'll have trouble catching us. But it only takes one 
race to make this a close battle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett, however, has been the most unlikely candidate to throw  
in a stinker this season. 
</P>
<P>
	His only bad effort came on opening week, here at the Daytona  
500, when he was involved in a multicar accident that knocked 
himself and several other contenders out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he has finished out of the top 10 only once, a  
16-race stretch of consistency unlike any the 15-year veteran can 
recall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't remember being involved in anything like it,'' Jarrett  
said. ``We've overcome some things where we shouldn't have finished 
in the top 10 and we did. We've done things we need to do to win 
championships. There have been days we needed all 500 miles, or all 
600 miles, to get the car right. But we continued to work on it and 
get it right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This race was won thanks to crew chief Todd Parrott's decision  
to turn Jarrett's last trip to the pits into a lightning-quick, 
fuel-only stop. It lasted just four seconds -- maybe not even that 
long -- and gave him just enough fuel to complete the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Todd said we were going to come in and put four seconds worth  
of fuel in,'' Jarrett said. ``That's about as quick a four seconds 
as I've ever seen. If they had that in the NBA, they wouldn't have 
gotten a shot off in that four seconds, but it worked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming out of the pits, Jarrett opened up a big lead on Rusty  
Wallace and the rest of the field. A pair of yellow flags tightened 
the gap, however. And when the final yellow came out at the end of 
lap 157, it was Jarrett trying to hold off Earnhardt for one more 
lap around the 2.5-mile trioval. 
</P>
<P>
	He did, then ran the last two laps of the race under yellow. So  
slim was the margin that Jarrett's car ran out of gasoline on his 
victory lap. It left some doubt as to whether he could have held 
Earnhardt off had the yellow not come out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it would have been any different,'' Jarrett  
said. ``Earnhardt wasn't getting much of a push from anybody, so I 
was able to keep him kind of where I needed to keep him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Naturally, Earnhardt disagreed. He had taken on two new tires on  
his final pit stop. It helped him move from sixth to second in the 
eight laps before the final yellow came out. 
</P>
<P>
	At the finish, he was bearing down on Jarrett, looking for his  
second straight victory on a restrictor-plate track. But The 
Intimidator, almost surely saving up steam for a challenge on the 
final lap, never got the chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think within a few more laps we would have gotten by  
Jarrett,'' Earnhardt said. ``He might have run out of gas, because 
he was really close. That caution really helped him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 12:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Needs State Help on Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Service was  
established last year to make sure dangerous people don't get their 
hands on guns, but officials say the system can't work without 
cooperation from the states. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI tries to weed out people with past convictions,  
outstanding felony warrants, restraining orders for domestic 
violence and other violations during its background checks for gun 
purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	But much of the information in state computers never reaches the  
FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can only check what's in there,'' says James E. Kessler,  
Jr., head of the FBI's Clarksburg, W.Va.-based background service, 
called the National Instant Check System or NICS. ``If it's not in 
there, it's not going to get checked,'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kessler said just 24 states provide information on restraining  
orders to federal authorities. Some don't provide information on 
mental illness or suspected gang participation because of privacy 
concerns. Also, states on average share less than one in five 
outstanding felony warrant records. 
</P>
<P>
	Kessler said NICS officials spend the bulk of their time dealing  
with the 5 percent of state records that arrive without 
dispositions, which tell whether a felony arrest resulted in 
conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts state Sen. Cheryl Jacques, who has sponsored  
legislation calling for her state to improve warrant tracking, says 
lack of cooperation can undermine the whole system. Massachusetts 
does not provide the FBI with information on restraining orders, 
and only 2,700 of the state's 70,000 outstanding felony warrants 
are in the FBI wanted list. 
</P>
<P>
	If the FBI has no record of him, someone wanted for armed  
robbery in Massachusetts ``can just go to New Hampshire, 15 minutes 
away, and purchase a gun,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Kessler says the FBI has blocked 48,000 gun purchases in nearly  
2.3 million background checks nationwide since NICS was created in 
November. States have conducted more than 2.4 million of their own 
tests, but usually use the NICS along with state records. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to remember that this is a voluntary system,''  
Kessler says. ``We can't force states to put information in 
there.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
