<HEADLINE> Rock Denies Interest in Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Comedian Chris Rock says he has no interest in  
politics, despite urgings from the Rev. Jesse Jackson that he 
become more involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in show business,'' Rock told TV Guide in its July 10  
issue. ``I wanna hang out with Janet Jackson, not Jesse Jackson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rock also reflected on the deaths of comedians Chris Farley and  
Phil Hartman, who he worked with on ``Saturday Night Live,'' 
calling them victims of ``the comedian curse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're performers -- a bunch of geeks no one liked,'' he said.  
``Now, people finally like us, and we're willing to put up with a 
tremendous amount... and make ourselves miserable, to maintain it. 
Then, you know, we explode. Our wives shoot us, we OD or 
whatever.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
