<DOCNO> APW19990705.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 10:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Medicare Policy Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elderly and disabled Americans who rack up  
unusually high bills for medicines would not be rescued by Medicare 
prescription drug coverage President Clinton has proposed. Many 
others already get better drug benefits as part of retirement 
packages. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton's proposed drug coverage could help many who have  
moderate drug costs and no coverage now or who buy comparatively 
expensive individual insurance policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``How good a deal it is sort of varies, depending on what you  
have now,'' said Margaret Davis, assistant director of the 
Institute for Medicare Practice at the Mount Sinai School of 
Medicine in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's proposal to add prescription drug coverage to  
Medicare, made public last week, would be available as an option to 
all 39 million elderly and disabled beneficiaries starting in 2002. 
People would have a one-year window to decide whether they want the 
drug benefit, either in 2002 or the year they become eligible for 
Medicare at age 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare now covers only drugs administered in hospitals or  
doctors offices. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who opt for the new benefit would pay a $24-a-month  
premium. In return, the government would pay half the price of 
their prescriptions up to a $1,000 annual cap on federal payments. 
</P>
<P>
	By 2008, the premium would rise to $44 a month and the maximum  
government payment to $2,500 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	For the one-third of Medicare beneficiaries without drug  
coverage now -- including many disabled Americans turned away by 
private insurers -- the new benefit would be a modest help. 
</P>
<P>
	Prescription costs per person for Medicare beneficiaries are  
around $600 per year, on average. Under Clinton's plan, someone 
whose drugs cost that much in 2002 would pay $588 -- the $288 annual 
premium plus $300 in cost sharing -- saving $12. 
</P>
<P>
	The maximum savings possible would be $712, for those with  
$2,000 or more in drug costs. About 13 percent of Medicare 
beneficiaries have drug bills that high. 
</P>
<P>
	For them, the help Clinton is offering will not go very far,  
consumer advocates say. 
</P>
<P>
	``That small percentage of people with big expenses, those are  
the people who need help the most,'' said Gail Shearer, director of 
health policy analysis for Consumers Union. ``But the problem 
politically is if you target the funds there, it's not going to be 
very popular.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's plan would provide more substantial help for those  
with incomes near the poverty level, who would pay no premium or 
cost-sharing. The administration also predicts that, as a large 
purchaser, Medicare will be able to negotiate drug discounts 
resulting in savings of 10 percent to 15 percent for all 
beneficiaries. 
</P>
<P>
	But the proposed Medicare benefit would be a step down for most  
of the 10 million retirees who get drug coverage from former 
employers. 
</P>
<P>
	``People covered by employer plans will be better off staying  
with the employer plans,'' said Richard Ostuw, global practice 
director for Watson Wyatt Worldwide consultants in Bethesda, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Most retirees who get drug coverage from large companies pay  
premiums of only a few dollars a month, cost-sharing is normally 
limited to a flat $5 to $10 charge regardless of the price of the 
prescription, and caps on insurance payments are unusual. 
</P>
<P>
	Retirees would be able to keep better employer-sponsored  
benefits since the Medicare drug coverage Clinton proposes would be 
voluntary. But Republican lawmakers critical of Clinton's plan 
worry that companies may feel they no longer must offer drug 
coverage to retirees if Medicare does. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will employers drop the currently provided retiree coverage  
for drugs when a universal new benefit is paid for by the 
government?'' wonders Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House 
Commerce Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants new financial incentives to help encourage  
companies to keep offering retiree drug benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, most of the 3 million Americans who now buy  
private individual insurance to supplement Medicare, known as 
Medigap, likely would prefer the benefits Clinton has proposed. 
Premiums for Medigap policies vary widely, but the portion 
accounting for drug benefits can range from $60 to $150 a month, 
according to estimates from the insurance industry and consumer 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	That's more than double Clinton's plan. Plus, Medigap requires a  
$250 deductible before coverage kicks in. Medicare would have no 
deductible. 
</P>
<P>
	Medigap does offer higher maximum reimbursements: $1,250 or  
$3,000 a year, depending on the policy. For that reason, some 
people with high drug costs might still find Medigap attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	Least certain is how Clinton's proposal would affect the 6  
million Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs. About two-thirds of HMOs 
now offer some prescription coverage as a perquoisite to attract 
older customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Clinton's plan, HMOs participating in Medicare would have  
to offer drug benefits. But it's unclear whether those that already 
do that would change their coverage. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
