<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 06:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Total Fina in Hostile Bid for Elf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French oil group Total Fina launched an unsolicited  
takeover bid on Monday for Elf Aquitaine. If successful, the 
combination would be the world's fourth largest oil company in 
terms of market capitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Total Fina said it was offering Elf shareholders  
four Total Fina shares for three Elf shares. The offer, worth 42 
billion euros ($42.94 billion), is conditional upon 66.7 percent 
acceptance by Elf shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	But Elf said it considered Total Fina's 4-for-3 share swap offer  
a hostile bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``This offer has not been the subject of any study or  
discussions with Elf's management and is therefore considered as 
being hostile,'' the company said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Elf doesn't believe the Total Fina offer is in its  
shareholders' best interests, pointing out that the value of Elf 
shares has doubled over the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elf management has continued to successfully follow a clear  
strategy over the past several years directed towards the creation 
of value and the development of the company's core businesses,'' 
Elf said. The Elf board will meet to discuss the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Total Fina Chairman Thierry Desmarest said: ``Joining the two  
companies will allow us to achieve pretax synergies expected to 
aggregate 1.2 billion euros ($1.17 billion) over a three-year 
period.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Total Fina added that the successful integration of the two  
groups ``would produce very strong earnings growth of at least 20 
percent a year, assuming a constant environment, over the coming 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new company would be Europe's third largest oil group after  
Royal Dutch Shell and BP Amoco. It would likely enjoy strong growth 
in oil output and be better able to compete with American and 
European rivals, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two groups have been under pressure to increase their  
critical mass amid rapid recent consolidation in the sector in the 
United States and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf, once the French state's largest concern, was privatized in  
1994. Total Fina is the product of Total's merger earlier this year 
with Belgium's Petrafina. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 12:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally higher  
Monday, with the key indexes both in Tokyo and Hong Kong rising to 
over 20-month highs on the back of record gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose  
202.59 points, or 1.13 percent, finishing at 18,135.06 -- its 
highest closing level since Sept. 25, 1997, when the index closed 
at 18,341.96. On Friday, the average closed up 71.72 points at 
17,932.47. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo stocks rose after a Bank of Japan survey showed business  
sentiment has improved. Prices were also boosted by Friday's gains 
on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average closed at a 
record-high 11,139.24 points, up 72.82. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank survey showed a rise in confidence at large Japanese  
businesses over the past three months -- the biggest advance since 
August 1994 -- prompting some investors to buy yen. Surveyed 
companies predicted that optimism will improve further by the time 
of the next survey in September, encouraging investors. 
</P>
<P>
	On the currency market, the U.S. dollar was quoted 122.58 yen in  
late-afternoon trading, up 1.50 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and 
above its level late Friday in New York of 121.01 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks surged for a second straight session.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chip rose 322.16 points, or 2.3 percent, to close at 
14,506.74, its highest level since Oct. 8, 1997. On Friday, the 
index had soared 652.44 points, or 4.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said investors continued to buy blue chips in reaction  
to Friday's gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong stocks have been climbing since last week following a  
small interest rate increase by the U.S. Federal Reserve, which 
hinted that it won't raise rates again soon. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean shares also closed sharply higher, with the main  
index surging 3.2 percent on expectations that the government will 
maintain low interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 29.42 points to to  
962.84, its highest close since May 14, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed slightly higher as bargain-hunting  
in laggard plastic and construction stocks offset profit-taking in 
technology issues. The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index rose 
29.80 points, or 0.3 percent, to 8,593.35. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly lower in  
absence of foreign buying. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index 
slipped 1.12 points, or 0.05 percent, to 2,140.80. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher, boosted by the latest  
cut in the Philippine central bank's key overnight rates and 
favorable June inflation data. The 30-company Philippine Stock 
Exchange Index rose 42.95 points, or 1.6 percent, to 2,621.67. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares closed higher, propelled by  
enthusiastic investor sentiment spilling over from Friday's record 
rally on Wall Street. The All Ordinaries Index rose 49.2 points, or 
1.6 percent, to 3,078.1. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Profit-taking pushed the main index slightly down.  
The Composite Index fell 1.44 points to 847.06. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly lower as the market  
succumbed to profit-taking. The Straits Times Index fell 11.01 
points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,211.44. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed lower. The Composite  
Index fell 5.394 points, or 0.8 percent, to 665.14. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices ended marginally lower on  
profit-taking. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index slipped 0.18 
point to 533.15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
