<DOCNO> APW19990705.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 07:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  A Closing Act at Wimbledon for Graf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Steffi Graf has said farewell to  
Wimbledon and the French Open. All that remains is her final 
goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no wave, no acknowledgment to the 14,000 fans after  
her 6-4, 7-5 loss to Lindsay Davenport in Sunday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	She said afterward this was her final match at the All England  
Club, but her conduct on Centre Court gave nothing away. Graf did 
not want a public display to detract from Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt it was her day and I wanted to keep it that way and not  
take anything away from her,'' Graf said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she won't be back, but said little else about her  
future as she spoke in a soft, measured voice. Playing the U.S. 
Open is in doubt, she said, although she plans to play ``several 
more tournaments,'' with word on her future coming in a few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will not comment on anything other than that. I have not had  
enough time to think about those things,'' Graf said. 
</P>
<P>
	When and where her final tournament will come -- or if Graf  
remains true to her word -- is anyone's guess. 
</P>
<P>
	Her compatriot Boris Becker said the same thing about Wimbledon  
two years ago, only to return this year and lose in the fourth 
round. This time he promised he'd played his last Wimbledon -- 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	``Becker said 99.9 percent and he was back two years later,''  
said NBC commentator John McEnroe, adding this ``is by no means a 
definite guarantee as far as I'm concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Graf's first loss in a Wimbledon final since 1987 -- the  
first time she reached the championship match. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old German has won seven Wimbledon singles titles,  
two short of Martina Navratilova's record of nine. Her 22 Grand 
Slam tournament singles titles are also two shy of Margaret's 
Court's record 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a lot of fun but, I guess, yes, there's going to be  
a certain time when I've got to move on with something else in my 
life,'' Graf said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, I'm a little sad about everything, which is normal  
for the moment,'' she said. ``But I still think that I feel ... a 
winner getting out of this tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A month ago, Graf won the French Open, then announced it was her  
last appearance at Roland Garros. At Wimbledon, she made her mind 
up before the two-week grass-court event to make this her last. A 
victory would not have changed things. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a decision and, you know, I've been pretty sure about it  
for a long time,'' she said. ``It's not something I just thought 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The WTA Tour guide devotes one page to most players, two to  
stars like Monica Seles. Graf gets three. The WTA Tour also put out 
a two-page synopsis of her major injuries and illnesses and listed 
21 -- almost equaling her Slams. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the turned professional in 1982, she's had right foot  
surgery twice, with other operations on her right hand, left knee, 
left foot and sinuses. She's also had a herniated disc and broken 
her right toe and right thumb. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a lot of injuries in the last several years, and that  
has something to do with all of this,'' said Graf, who played the 
final with her left thigh wrapped and pulled out of mixed doubles 
with McEnroe because of the injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Her first Grand Slam tournament title was the French Open in  
1987. In '88 she won the Grand Slam -- Wimbledon and the Australian, 
French and U.S. Opens -- and the next year again reached all four 
finals, losing only in the French. Three other times she won three 
of the four major tournaments ('93, '95, '96). 
</P>
<P>
	Injuries have hurt. So have personal problems.  
</P>
<P>
	Her father, Peter, was released from prison in April 1998 after  
serving 15 months for tax evasion handling his daughter's tennis 
winnings, which are $21 million going into this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf pointed to her '92 victory over Monica Seles and her '91  
win over Gabriela Sabatini as her two most memorable Wimbledon 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went through a lot of struggles during a certain period,''  
Graf said, alluding to problems surrounding her father. ``The one 
match that I played against Gaby for me was personally a big one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While her father was serving prison time, Graf underwent left  
knee surgery in June 1997, keeping her out of Wimbledon and the 
next three major tournaments. She returned last year, but was 
knocked out in the third round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the last few weeks have been pretty amazing,'' she  
said. ``Who would have thought I would be doing so well? It's 
obvious that I'm disappointed about losing the final, but I do have 
to say ... it been tough getting there, but it's also been ... 
great here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 21:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hershiser Back on One Day of Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- At age 40, Orel Hershiser will have a first  
Tuesday: starting with just one day of rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Mets reshuffled their pitching rotation following  
Monday's 2-1 win over Montreal, and Hershiser (8-5) will start 
against Carl Pavano (6-6) instead of rookie of Octavio Dotel (1-1). 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Hershiser allowed four homers for the second time in  
484 career appearances, giving up six runs and six hits in 2 2-3 
innings during a 7-6 win over Atlanta. He made 52 pitches, and 
Tuesday would have been his regular day to throw. 
</P>
<P>
	Mets manager Bobby Valentine said giving Masato Yoshii and his  
ailing knee an extra day between starts was the reason for the 
reshuffle, but it's logical to assume he didn't want Dotel pitching 
against the New York Yankees on Sunday in the final game before the 
All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever Bobby says is what happened,'' Hershiser said, trying  
to diffuse any possible controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	While he's never started twice in three days, Hershiser came  
back on three days' rest against the Mets in Game 3 of the 1988 NL 
championship series after starting the opener, then saved Game 4 
for the Los Angeles Dodgers the following night. 
</P>
<P>
	He then came back on just two days' rest, pitching a five-hit  
shutout to beat the Mets 6-0 in Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just thank God I have an arm that can bounce back and shut  
out the Mets with two days rest,'' Hershiser said then. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine approached him about another quick turnaround before  
Monday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was, `This is a possibility. Can you do it?' '' he recalled  
the manager saying. Hershiser's response was: ``Whatever you 
think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hershiser seemed to take it in stride. Starters, he said, long  
to be everyday players. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting because you get to do something you never do,''  
he said, ``unless you get bombed as a starter and get right back 
out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the change, Dotel will pitch Wednesday against Dan Smith  
(1-1) and Yoshii (6-7) will close out the series against the Expos 
on Thursday instead of Al Leiter (7-6). 
</P>
<P>
	Leiter, who beat the Yankees on June 6 to end the Mets'  
eight-game losing streak and start them on a 20-8 stretch, will 
open the Subway Series on Friday, followed by Rick Reed (6-3) and 
Hershiser. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 07:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
