<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 23:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hershiser Back on One Day of Rest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eleven years later, Orel Hershiser has a chance  
to show whether he's still the ``Bulldog.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hershiser, who made five starts and one relief appearance during  
a 16-day span in the 1988 postseason, will have a career first 
tonight: starting with just one day of rest. 
</P>
<P>
	And he's doing it at age 40, on a night when it's expected to be  
close to 100 degrees with high humidity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's exciting because you get to do something you never do,''  
he said, ``unless you get bombed as a starter and get right back 
out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Hershiser allowed four homers for the second time in  
484 career appearances, giving up six runs and six hits in 2 2-3 
innings during the New York Mets' 7-6 win over Atlanta. He made 52 
pitches, and today would have been his regular day to throw. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Mets manager Bobby Valentine reshuffled his pitching  
rotation following Monday's 2-1 win over Montreal and Hershiser 
(8-5) will start tonight in place of rookie Octavio Dotel (1-1) 
against Carl Pavano (6-6). 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said giving Masato Yoshii and his ailing knee an extra  
day between starts was the reason for the change, but it's logical 
to assume Valentine didn't want Dotel pitching against the New York 
Yankees on Sunday in the final game before the All-Star break. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever Bobby says is what happened,'' Hershiser said, trying  
to diffuse any possible controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	While he's never started twice in three days, Hershiser started  
three times on three days' rest and once on two days' rest during 
the 1988 postseason, and even made a relief appearance the day 
after a start. 
</P>
<P>
	In the NL championship series against the Mets, he failed to get  
a decision in Game 1 on Oct. 4 or Game 3 on Oct. 8, but then 
relieved in Game 4 on Oct. 9 before tossing a five-hit shutout that 
led the Los Angeles Dodgers to victory in Game 7 on Oct. 12. And 
during Game 5, he warmed up in the bullpen without getting in. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, on Oct. 16, he pitched a three-hit shutout against Oakland  
in Game 2 of the World Series. He closed out the Dodgers' last 
World Series title with a four-hit 5-2 win in Game 5 on Oct. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just thank God I have an arm that can bounce back and shut  
out the Mets with two days rest,'' Hershiser said after he was 
voted Most Valuable Player of both the playoffs and the World 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Hershiser was nicknamed ``Bulldog'' by Dodgers manager Tommy  
Lasorda for his determination. He ended the regular season with a 
record 59 consecutive scoreless innings, and including the 
postseason allowed five earned runs in his final 101 2-3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine approached him about another quick turnaround before  
Monday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was, `This is a possibility. Can you do it?' '' he recalled  
the manager saying. Hershiser's response was: ``Whatever you 
think.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the change, Dotel will pitch Wednesday against Dan Smith  
(1-1) and Yoshii (6-7) will close out the series against the Expos 
on Thursday instead of Al Leiter (7-6). 
</P>
<P>
	Leiter, who beat the Yankees on June 6 to end the Mets'  
eight-game losing streak and start them on their winning ways, will 
open the Subway Series on Friday, followed by Rick Reed (6-3) and 
Hershiser. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 10:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Business Sentiment Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Major Japanese companies are growing more confident  
about the economy though a growing number are reluctant to spend 
more, according to a closely watched survey released Monday by the 
Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In its quarterly ``tankan'' survey, the Bank of Japan reported  
that sentiment among large manufacturers showed the biggest 
improvement since August 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, stocks surged to their highest level in more than a  
year and a half as the report raised hopes that the long ailing 
economy was on the mend. 
</P>
<P>
	Optimism rose among small- and medium-sized manufacturers as  
well, marking the first time since November 1996 that the bank's 
index for business sentiment improved for all companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses were more optimistic about future conditions,  
predicting they would improve by the next survey in three months, 
the BOJ said. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey ``clearly shows that the economy has hit bottom,''  
said Takashi Imai, chairman of the Japan Federation of Economic 
Organizations, a powerful business group. 
</P>
<P>
	The growing confidence follows a surprise economic growth spurt  
and a drop in unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's gross domestic product -- the measure of all goods and  
services produced within its borders -- grew 1.9 percent for the 
first quarter of the year after more than a year of recession. The 
unemployment rate fell to 4.6 percent in May from a record high of 
4.8 percent the previous two months. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the benchmark Nikkei Stock Average added 202.59  
points, or 1.13 percent, to close at 18,135.06 -- its highest close 
since Sept. 25, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the survey showed improvement from the one in March,  
there were troubling signs as well. 
</P>
<P>
	A majority of companies were still pessimistic about economic  
conditions and a growing number said they planned to cut capital 
investment in the year ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey showed large manufacturers were planning to slash  
spending by 11 percent this year, compared to an estimated cut of 
9.5 percent in the March survey. 
</P>
<P>
	Capital spending ``went in the wrong direction,'' said Ken  
Landon, a senior currency strategist at Deutsche Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	To measure business sentiment, the tankan survey calculates the  
percentage of firms that forecast economic conditions will improve 
minus the percentage that predict conditions will worsen. A 
negative number means pessimists outnumber optimists. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest report, the index among large manufacturers  
reached minus 37 -- still negative, but a higher number than in the 
previous survey, when the figure came to minus 47. 
</P>
<P>
	The index of business sentiment has not entered positive  
territory since September, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank surveyed 9,366 companies for the latest report. A  
central bank official estimated that about 80 percent of the 
respondents answered the survey after the announcement of growth in 
the gross domestic product. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 16:43:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Firefighters Control Utah Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUREKA, Utah (AP) -- Winds died down and temperatures cooled  
Monday, allowing 400 firefighters to get a handle on a fire that 
has burned more than 61,400 acres of dry grass and trees in central 
Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews carried water by hand up steep mountain areas that  
water-dropping helicopters could not reach. The fire, burning in 
pinion pine, cheat grass and juniper trees since Friday, was 
expected to be controlled by Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire, near the neighboring towns of Eureka and Mammoth,  
about 55 miles south of Salt Lake City, twice drove residents from 
their homes over the weekend. No one was injured and only three 
abandoned shacks burned. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire began in a patch of grass along some railroad tracks  
and was fanned by 50 mph wind gusts and hot, dry weather. It spread 
when a tanker truck containing 11,000 gallons of diesel fuel 
exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of firefighters also fought wildfires of around 3,000  
acres each in dry areas of central and southern Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, firefighters also battled an 8,000-acre fire spanning  
western Colorado and eastern Utah. The massive blaze -- two fires 
that were pushed together Sunday afternoon by hot winds -- was 
fueled by tinder-dry sage, pinion pine and juniper. 
</P>
<P>
	``The winds are the driving force right now,'' Lynn Kolund, fire  
management officer for the Bureau of Land Management in Grand 
Junction, Colo. ``The winds plus the remote and difficult terrain 
are really keeping us from getting a hold of this one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Northern California, a controlled burn that got out of  
control and consumed 2,000 acres was mostly contained. Two dozen 
homes in the mountain hamlet of Lewiston were damaged, at a cost of 
$1.6 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 20:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Thunderstorms rolled across the upper Great Lakes and northern  
New England on Monday, and hot, damp air covered much of the East. 
</P>
<P>
	An area of strong thunderstorms and heavy rain spread from  
northern Minnesota into northern sections of Wisconsin and 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 7 inches of rain fell Sunday and Monday around northern  
Minnesota's cities of Hibbing and Virginia, and flooding forced 
residents from their homes and swamped roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Wind gusting to 80 mph knocked down power lines and trees. Late  
Monday, authorities evacuated 14 injured people from the Boundary 
Waters Canoe Area after very strong winds swept through. 
</P>
<P>
	West of that area of rough weather, scattered showers and a few  
thunderstorms moved across North Dakota into northwestern 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Another area of thunderstorms and locally heavy rain moved  
across northern sections of New York, Vermont and New Hampshire 
into Maine, where high wind uprooted large trees and ripped down 
power lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounded like a train was going right through our house. The  
floor was rumbling right under our feet,'' said Sherry Chase of 
Moscow, Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, a few showers and thunderstorms developed over parts  
of Arizona and New Mexico, and along the Gulf Coast from Texas to 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Isolated thunderstorms were possible over parts of Arkansas,  
eastern Oklahoma and eastern Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure over the Southeast produced hot, humid weather  
over most of the region east of the Mississippi River. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperature records for the date included 103 at Newark, N.J.;  
94 at Portland, Maine; 101 at New York City; and 102 at 
Washington's National Airport. Bridgeport, Conn., hit 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 24 at Stanley, Idaho, to an afternoon high of 103 at 
Newark. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 11:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  China 5, Norway 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- China coach Ma Yuanan doesn't expect the  
Wo,0573men's World Cup final to be a repeat of his team's Fourth 
of July humbling of Norway.  
</P>
<P>
	He'd be happy enough if it was a repeat of April 25.  
</P>
<P>
	That's the last time China met the United States team that it  
will face again in Saturday's World Cup gold medal game in 
Pasadena, Calif. And China won that one 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``China has beaten the U.S.A. already twice (this year),''  
Norway coach Per-Mathias Hogmo said Sunday after China shut out the 
Norwegians 5-0 at Foxboro Stadium to advance to the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they will be the favorites in the final. But they will  
meet a very enthusiastic U.S. team. So I think that will be an 
interesting fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Liu Ailing and Sun Wen scored two goals apiece -- scoring once  
each in the first 14 minutes to give China control early on a hot, 
sweaty night. The Chinese took a 3-0 lead six minutes into the 
second half on Liu's second goal, which was assisted by Sun. 
</P>
<P>
	And Norway still hadn't gotten a shot on goal.  
</P>
<P>
	``We were able to dictate the way the game was played,'' China  
goalkeeper Gao Hong said. ``We play with a sense of spiritual 
unity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was enough to win by the biggest margin in World Cup  
semifinal history and match the largest defeat in Norway soccer 
history. The loss left the Norwegians out of the final for the 
first time in the three World Cups. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had no possibility to show our best'' because of the early  
deficit, said Norway defender Linda Medalen, whose team will play 
for third place against Brazil, a 2-0 loser to the United States 
earlier Sunday in San Jose, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The championship game will be a rematch of the 1996 Olympic gold  
medal game that the United States won 2-1. Since then, the teams 
have met six more times, with the United States holding the 
advantage, three games to two, with one tie. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt that the United States is one of the  
strongest teams in the world,'' the Chinese coach said. ``But the 
Chinese have played them three times (this year) and hold a 2-1 
advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans will have a tough time if China dominates the ball  
as it did Sunday in stopping Norway's 10-game World Cup winning 
streak -- a streak that dates to the final of the 1991 tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a hard game'' for the Americans, said the  
34-year-old defender, who is one of three Norway players remaining 
from the 1991 team. ``The two best teams are in the final, no doubt 
about that. ... I look forward to seeing (it).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gao, the Chinese keeper, was rarely tested in the first half  
when Norway was outshot 11-0. The Norwegians had a 12-9 shooting 
advantage in the second half as they substituted and strategized to 
increase their offense, to no avail. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, China closed in often on Norwegian keeper Bente  
Nordby, scoring on its first two chances with goals by Sun in the 
third minute and Liu in the 14th. 
</P>
<P>
	Six minutes into the second half, Liu scored again with a  
12-yard left-footed volley after a Norwegian defender tried to 
clear a corner kick into the box. Fan Yunjie made it 4-0 in the 
65th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun also scored on a penalty kick after a hand ball in the box  
in the 72nd minute to tie Sissi of Brazil for the tournament lead 
with seven goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``She hasn't thought about that (the scoring lead) at all,'' Sun  
said through an interpreter. ``Her whole outlook has been to play 
with the team and to win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 11:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
