<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 23:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Mariners Ballpark Dedicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The hot dogs are tastier, the seats more  
comfortable, the views much better and the open air glorious, 
Seattle Mariners fans said Monday at the dedication of their new 
ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	So what if service at the concession stands was slow and the  
relish table ill-designed? 
</P>
<P>
	A day after Ken Griffey Jr. first weighed in on the side of  
public officials in a dispute over financing, a crowd estimated at 
15,000 cheered the impending return of outdoor baseball after more 
than two decades in the Kingdome. 
</P>
<P>
	The question of who should pay for $100 million in cost overruns  
on the $517 million project seemed almost lost in the shadows. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care, just as long as they play ball here,'' said Rob  
Eason of Spanaway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're back to the way baseball ought to be played --  
outdoors, on the grass,'' Orlin VanWieringen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners could hardly have ordered more perfect weather for  
the festivities, a cloudless sky with a light breeze and 
temperatures edging into the 70s -- the warmest, sunniest weather in 
more than three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``For too long we have suffered with less than the best. Today  
we have the best,'' Mayor Paul Schell said. ``It's time to 
celebrate a great stadium that all of our children and our 
children's children can enjoy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute was evident only in the lackluster applause and a  
few boos for club president Chuck Armstrong, who ignored the snub 
and proclaimed, ``What a great day out for baseball! Ain't baseball 
great?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong was a last-minute stand-in for Mariners chairman John  
Ellis, who has borne most of the load in the club's demand for $60 
million in additional public funding. 
</P>
<P>
	An article Sunday in The Seattle Times said Ellis and others  
suggested the Mariners might trade Griffey or Alex Rodriguez if the 
demand was rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time this team has something come up, it's always me and  
Alex to blame,'' Griffey told The News Tribune of Tacoma, Wash., on 
Sunday after a phone call from ESPN. ``We love the game. We love 
playing in front of 40,000, 50,000 fans at home. Why does John 
Ellis want to make it so hard for us to bring those people out? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not us asking for more money here. I've been here 11  
years, Jay Buhner has been here 11 years. How much money do we have 
to defer? I deferred $5 million in my salary and offered to defer 
$10 million. They turned it down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team was in Anaheim to play the Angels on Monday night, so  
the players missed the dedication. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 23:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush To Forgo Pay When Out of Tex. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush says he'll go off  
the Texas payroll when he's out of state campaigning for the 
Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	When Bush is out of Texas for an entire day, Republican Lt. Gov.  
Rick Perry becomes acting governor under state law and receives an 
additional $316.01 a day, the same amount as Bush's salary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because the lieutenant governor is paid in my absence, I don't  
think it's appropriate for the taxpayers of Texas to pay my salary 
twice,'' said Bush, who receives $115,345 a year as governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry only gets the additional salary if Bush is out of state  
for a full day -- from midnight to midnight, according to the 
governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The change announced Monday is retroactive. Bush, the  
front-runner for the GOP nomination, will reimburse the state 
$2,212.07, representing the salary he received during the seven 
days he campaigned outside Texas last month, according to the 
governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Fresh from celebrating Fourth of July in New Hampshire Sunday,  
Bush will leave Austin again today to make campaign swings through 
Denver, Salt Lake City, and Portland, Ore. He's set to return 
Thursday night or Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	During his first stop in Denver, Bush will receive the  
endorsement of several of the state's key Hispanic leaders, 
including some Democrats, his campaign reported. Later in the 
evening, he will attend a fund-raising reception that is expected 
to add more than $150,000 to his already record-setting campaign 
coffers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's campaign stops have included fund-raisers throughout Iowa  
and Florida. In California last week he announced his campaign has 
collected a record $36.25 million in its first six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-term governor also reported he has no personal debts and  
a financial portfolio that includes at least $7 million in U.S. 
Treasury notes and a diversified trust worth at least $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush has pledged to go without his gubernatorial salary  
while campaigning out of state, he will continue using bodyguards 
from the Texas Department of Public Safety and the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Bush is elected president, the state will continue to  
provide security until he leaves the Governor's Mansion for the 
White House, said Tom Vinger, a spokesman for the Texas Department 
of Public Safety. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
