<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 04:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar climbed Monday to a one-and-a-half  
month high against the yen after intervention by Japan's central 
bank. Tokyo's main stock index closed sharply higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.58 yen in late-afternoon trading, up 1.50  
yen from late Friday in Tokyo and above its level late Friday in 
New York of 121.01 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average added 202.59 points, or 1.13 percent,  
finishing at 18,135.06 -- its highest closing level since Sept. 25, 
1997, when the index closed at 18,341.96. On Friday, the average 
closed up 71.72 points to 17,932.47. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, a senior government official confirmed in  
an unusually quick admission that the Bank of Japan stepped into 
markets to weaken the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we took action in the markets,'' said Haruhiko Kuroda,  
head of the international bureau at the Finance Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank reportedly made several rounds of interventions  
following the release of the BOJ's closely-watched ``tankan'' 
quarterly survey of corporations, which showed business sentiment 
improving. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey showed that confidence at large Japanese businesses  
posted its biggest advance since August 1994 -- prompting some 
investors to buy yen. Surveyed companies predicted that optimism 
will improve further by the time of the next survey in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial authorities, concerned the yen's rise would  
slow the nation's economic recovery, sold yen to buy between $1 
billion and $2 billion, the Nihon Keizai newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	A higher yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad, and  
reduces dollar-denominated earnings at Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the government may be unable to stem a rise in the yen,  
dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The potential for a yen rise is fairly large after the  
improved tankan data,'' said Shigeru Hashimoto, a senior trader at 
Sanwa Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 120.90 yen and 122.87 yen in Monday's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 125.57 yen, up from  
123.86 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices surged on the tankan result as well  
as the record high Wall Street closing on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 717.38 million shares, up from 705.03 million shares 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 712 to 503, while 117  
issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 26.42 points, or 1.81 percent, to 
1,486.58. The TOPIX closed up 12.75 points, or 0.88 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government bond fell to  
1.6150 percent from Friday's finish of 1.6600 percent, driving its 
price up to 101.61 yen from 101.21 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
