<HEADLINE> Freight Trains Collide in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Two Union Pacific freight trains  
crashed head-on early Monday, derailing nine engines, spilling 
about 10,000 gallons of fuel and injuring two crewmen who leaped 
from each train before impact. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the injured crewmen was in serious but stable condition  
with a broken ankle and cuts. The other man had minor bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	A preliminary investigation indicated one train operator ran a  
red light, police Sgt. Mitch Spike said. Sgt. Patrick Williams 
estimated that the trains were traveling between 15 mph and 20 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Union Pacific Railroad spokesman Mike Furtney would not comment.  
  	   	
</P>
