<HEADLINE> European Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher Monday, with oil,  
telecommunications and chemical stocks leading. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index extended gains with a 1.9 percent  
advance, and earned itself a new record high. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street was closed for a public holiday.  
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Energy index registered its biggest percentage  
gain on record, up 4.3 percent, after the Paris-Brussels group, 
Total Fina, made a hostile share bid for smaller French rival Elf 
Aquitaine with a view to creating the world's fourth leading oil 
company in terms of market share. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf closed up 22 percent, at EUR177.30. Total Fina ended up 50  
cents at EUR128.50. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris CAC 40 index ended 1.7 percent higher, Milan's MIBtel  
index rose 1.9 percent, and Madrid's IBEX-35 index was up 1.5 
percent. London's FTSE-100 index was up 1.5 percent, just short of 
a new closing record high. 
</P>
<P>
	The bid comes after a major appreciation this year in the oil  
price, but some oil sector investors reckon corporate strategies 
are unaffected by that. 
</P>
<P>
	The oil-influenced Oslo bourse was more subdued, the All-Share  
index rising only 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Chemical stocks also were buoyed by London press reports that  
local stock BOC Group is ripe for merger. BOC is seen as a takeover 
target for Paris rival L'Air Liquide. 
</P>
<P>
	Automotives' rebound Monday was helped by rumors that tiremaker  
Continental could replace chemicals group Hoechst in Germany's 
Xetra DAX, when the index's composition is revised July 20. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
