<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Rejects David Duke's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A Confederate heritage group fighting to  
return Gen. Robert E. Lee's portrait to a downtown tourist 
attraction is getting some unwanted support from former Ku Klux 
Klan leader David Duke. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke said Monday he plans to visit the former Confederate  
capital July 15 to weigh in on the Lee controversy and urge whites 
to preserve their heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Black people are organized to do what they want,'' Duke said.  
``It's important for white Southerners to organize or this kind of 
thing is going to happen again and again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brag Bowling, a Sons of Confederate Veterans brigade commander,  
said Duke would only ``make the situation worse. The last thing 
Richmond needs is racial strife.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The portrait of Lee was removed from a history exhibit at  
Richmond's Canal Walk just before the project's June 4 grand 
opening. A black member of City Council said the portrait was 
offensive to many blacks and threatened to organize a boycott of 
the riverfront development. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sons of Confederate Veterans and others, some holding  
Confederate flags or wearing stars-and-bars lapel stickers, 
protested the removal of the portrait. 
</P>
<P>
	A committee of city leaders has since recommended that a  
different Lee portrait illustrating the Confederate hero's ties to 
Richmond be added to the floodwall gallery. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowling said he fears Duke's involvement will switch the focus  
back to race and undermine the proposed compromise. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
