<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Agent Denies Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- A sports agent under investigation for  
allegedly giving cash to former college football stars at Florida, 
South Carolina and LSU before their eligibility expired denied 
making illegal payments to entice players to sign with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Agent William ``Tank'' Black, in a formal response to the NFL  
Players Association's disciplinary complaint accusing him of 
recruiting violations, produced statements and affidavits from six 
players all denying any illegal payments were made to them. 
</P>
<P>
	Black and attorney Leonard Mungo will deliver the response,  
which was obtained by The Associated Press on Monday, to the NFLPA 
on Tuesday. Neither Black nor Mungo would comment on the response 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Statements from former Gators players Ike Hilliard, Reidel  
Anthony, Mike Peterson and Jacquez Green and affidavits from former 
Gator Fred Taylor and former LSU running back Kevin Faulk all 
denied payments were made. Black represents all those players 
except Peterson. 
</P>
<P>
	Another former Florida player, Johnny Rutledge, has admitted  
publicly that he accepted $500 per month from Black and that he and 
former Gators Jevon Kearse and Reggie McGrew all made sworn 
statements admitting the same. The three players and Peterson 
initially signed with Black, but later fired him. 
</P>
<P>
	Black's response referred to statements given under oath in  
April by Rutledge, Kearse and McGrew stating they, in fact, had not 
accepted any money. 
</P>
<P>
	NFLPA attorney Richard Berthelsen said Monday he was not aware  
of any written statement from the players exonerating Black. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only statement I'm aware of is one Johnny Rutledge has  
made to the contrary,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFLPA alleged that Black and an employee, Alfred Twitty,  
provided payments to former Florida and South Carolina players and, 
``on information and belief,'' to former players from LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	Black's reply included a sworn affidavit from Twitty, who said  
he does not recruit athletes for the agent and has never given 
money or anything of value to induce players to sign with Black. 
Twitty is a former football player at North Carolina A&AMP;T who joined 
Black's agency, Professional Management Inc., in 1996. He works out 
of Tampa. 
</P>
<P>
	In his response, Black goes point by point through the eight  
allegations brought by the NFLPA when it issued the complaint May 
19. The most serious allegations involve providing cash and cars to 
former college players. 
</P>
<P>
	``Black has not done anything wrong or broken any rules,'' the  
response reads. ``Yet, the NFLPA has singled out Black and marked 
him as though he has been tried for and convicted of a crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The union could revoke his license if it finds him guilty.  
</P>
<P>
	University of Florida police are also investigating Black. He  
would face up to five years in prison and a $5,000 fine if found 
guilty of violating the state's agent law. 
</P>
<P>
	In his response to the NFLPA, Black also produced bank records  
and sworn statements from car dealers showing that he did not 
arrange to buy automobiles for former Florida players before their 
eligibility expired. 
</P>
<P>
	Black submitted a notarized statement from a Mercedes dealer in  
Columbia stating that Rutledge spent three hours on the car lot on 
Jan. 4 -- two days after Florida's final game in the Orange Bowl -- 
shopping for a car. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank statements show Rutledge took a loan for $69,527 the same  
day to purchase a 1999 Mercedes S420V. 
</P>
<P>
	Black also submitted a statement from a Lexus dealer in Columbia  
who said he sold McGrew a car on Jan. 6. Records from the same bank 
show a loan dated Jan. 6 to McGrew for $60,998. 
</P>
<P>
	Black submitted records of a $66,350 loan taken out by Peterson  
on Jan. 4 to buy a 1998 Landrover. 
</P>
<P>
	He also provided records regarding the purchase of a Mercedes  
for Kearse. Black claims the $133,000 car was bought in Atlanta on 
Dec. 31, but never made it into Kearse's possession until after the 
Orange Bowl. Motor vehicle records in Florida show Kearse owned the 
car before the bowl game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can get a lot of documentation showing how you  
legitimately purchased cars for college players,'' said Berthelsen, 
who had not seen the response as of Monday. ``But the heart of this 
case is about paying cash to college athletes. How does he get 
around that?'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the reply, Black claims the union and other agents started a  
conspiracy to force him out of business. Those are the same type of 
claims Black made in a federal lawsuit he filed against the NFLPA 
two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Berthelsen said there was no such conspiracy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
