<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 14:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Kerrey Endorses Bill Bradley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLIVE, Iowa (AP) -- Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley said  
Monday he gains invaluable insight from an experienced former 
Democratic presidential candidate in collecting the endorsement of 
Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is very, very good day for the Bradley campaign,'' he  
said. ``We got a big boost today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley and Kerrey formally announced the endorsement in  
Nebraska and in Iowa, where precinct caucuses launch the 
presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrey has ``been through this process before, he's run for  
president of the United States before,'' said Bradley. ``He 
understands the difficulty of getting your arms around a country as 
big and diverse as this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrey's endorsement makes him the second current senator to  
back Bradley, joining Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. Bradley is the only 
announced opponent of Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement by the two-term Nebraska senator and former  
governor isn't surprising. He has had tensions with the Clinton 
administration, and was close to Bradley when they were Senate 
colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Any differences with Clinton and Gore were papered over during  
Monday's announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm endorsing Bill Bradley for president not because I dislike  
Al Gore, I like Al Gore a lot,'' said Kerrey. ``For me the choice 
is between two friends, the choice is between two able leaders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most polls have shown Gore with a solid lead in the race for the  
Democratic nomination, although Bradley is lurking as a threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrey sought the Democratic presidential nomination in 1992,  
and flirted with the idea of running again in 2000. In bowing out, 
he cited Bradley's presence in the race as a reason, arguing that 
Democrats were being offered a choice. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been a leader on race, he's been a leader on some of the  
most contentious issues of our day,''' said Kerrey. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrey has campaigned frequently in Iowa, and built a network of  
supporters that could be helpful to Bradley. About 100 people 
gathered for a sweltering backyard barbecue to hear Kerrey's 
endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Kerrey's backing comes from those impressed with his  
military background, including his award of the Medal of Honor for 
heroism in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of fake celebrities in the world today, but  
Bob Kerrey is a genuine American hero,'' said Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	In acknowledging the endorsement, Bradley vowed to stick with  
his policy of not accepting political action committee money. ``I'm 
trying to do this differently. I'm not doing any of the 
legal-illegal loopholes in the campaign finance laws,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that stance, Bradley has raised more than $11 million,  
compared with Gore's $18 million, which has helped his campaign 
gain credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in Omaha, Bradley said Kerrey's role in his campaign  
would be ``as large a role as he chooses,'' but he did not 
elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked, Kerrey all but ruled out being Bradley's running  
mate, saying that out of fairness to Nebraskans, he preferred to 
focus on his race for the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be difficult, but not impossible'' to run  
simultaneously for the vice presidency and the Senate, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 13:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
