<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush To Forgo Pay When Out of Tex. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush said Monday that he will  
forgo his gubernatorial salary -- $316.01 a day -- when he campaigns 
outside Texas for the Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	When Bush is out of state for an entire day, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry  
is elevated under state law to acting governor and paid an 
additional $316.01 a day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because the Lt. Governor is paid in my absence, I don't think  
it's appropriate for the taxpayers of Texas to pay my salary 
twice,'' said Bush, who is paid $115,345 a year as governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry only gets the additional salary if Bush is out of state  
the entire day -- from midnight to midnight, according to the 
governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	The change announced Monday is retroactive. Bush, the  
front-runner for the GOP nomination, will reimburse the state 
$2,212.07, representing the salary he received during the seven 
days he campaigned outside Texas last month, according to the 
governor's office. 
</P>
<P>
	Fresh from celebrating Fourth of July in New Hampshire on  
Sunday, Bush will leave Austin again Tuesday to make campaign 
swings through Denver, Salt Lake City, and Portland, Ore. He 
returns Thursday night or Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush has pledged to go without his gubernatorial salary  
while campaigning out of state, he will continue to use bodyguards 
supplied by the Texas Department of Public Safety and the Texas 
Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing security concerns, Bush aides and state officials decline  
to say how many guards travel with the governor or how much it 
costs Texas taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Department of Public Safety has always protected the  
state's governor,'' said Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	While traveling with Bush, the bodyguards fly on the governor's  
plane, which is paid for by the campaign, according to Bush's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Vinger, Department of Public Safety spokesman, said the  
state has had to increase the pool of officers trained for Bush's 
security as his travel schedule intensified. Part of the increase 
goes to Lt. Gov. Perry, who becomes eligible for bodyguards when 
Bush is out of town and he steps in as acting governor, Vinger 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if Bush is elected president, the state will continue to  
provide security until he leaves the Governor's Mansion for the 
White House, Vinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be with the governor as long as he is governor,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 05:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Is Star in Education Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Humongous Entertainment is building a reputation for doing  
education software right and pricing it fairly. This probably means 
they'll sell a lot of Blue's 123 Time Activities, a 
Windows-Macintosh CD-ROM aimed at preschoolers and priced at 
$19.99. 
</P>
<P>
	For those living without benefit of toddlers, Blue is a dog. A  
blue dog, not unexpectedly, who stars in Blue's Clues, a preschool 
television show by Nickelodeon. Her mission here involves pre-math 
skills and is aimed at the 3- to 6-year age group. 
</P>
<P>
	The central theme is that of a backyard fair. Blue helps the  
child complete various activities, which are rewarded in Blue 
Dollars that may be exchanged for prizes in the prize tent. 
</P>
<P>
	The educational concepts being delivered include pattern  
recognition, weight and measurement, simple addition and 
subtraction, sorting and classifying, prediction and estimation. 
</P>
<P>
	All of this comes in a giggle-centric, kid-smart way that is a  
visual and auditory delight. The animations are charming and 
simple, with bold, bright backgrounds. And the user interface 
accurately reflects the needs of the target audience. Directions 
are clear, cursors and navigation icons are large and easy to find. 
Instructions may be repeated simply by moving the cursor over the 
animation that first gave them. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all the activities are slam-dunk easy. In one card game  
against a teddy bear, the idea was to match either the shape or the 
number until you matched out all five cards dealt you. Three 
triangles, for example could be ``matched'' by one triangle (same 
shape) or three squares (same number). If you had no matches in 
your hand and less than five cards, you had to draw from the pack. 
</P>
<P>
	I thought it sounded simple. Then the bear won. Twice. My ego  
wouldn't risk a third try and I didn't have a toddler handy, so 
that part of the software remains unconquered. I will let it be 
known, however, that I was a standout on the number lines at 
``Mother May I?'' 
</P>
<P>
	System requirements are modest. For the Windows herd, Pentium 90  
or better, 16 megabytes of RAM, quad-speed CD-ROM. Macintosh users 
face the same memory and CD-ROM requirements, and should be running 
at least a 90 megahertz Power PC and System 7.5.3. Sound capability 
is assumed for both machines. 
</P>
<P>
	Humongous Entertainment's products are widely available at  
retail. If you live where the bears are unlikely to start retailing 
software, it's also available on line at humongous.com, or by 
telephone at (800) 499-8386. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. Send them to Larry Blasko,  
AP, 50 Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020-1666. Or e-mail via 
the Internet lblasko@ap.org. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
  	   	
