<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Holiday Heat Wilts the East  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Millions sweltered as record heat with high  
humidity wilted the East today. Heat advisories were posted by the 
National Weather Service from the Mississippi Valley to the East 
Coast. High temperatures and humidity created heat indexes of up to 
110 and more. Temperature records for the date included 103 at 
Newark, N.J.; 94 at Portland, Maine; 101 at New York City; and 102 
at Washington's National Airport. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Going to Poorest Areas  
</P>
<P>
	HAZARD, Ky. (AP) -- President Clinton today began a four-day tour  
of some of America's poorest spots. With Agriculture Secretary Dan 
Glickman and Gov. Paul Patton of Kentucky, Clinton launched his 
trip. About 2,000 people waited hours in blazing heat to glimpse 
the president at Hazard, Ky. His trip to six states is designed to 
highlight legislation that would help leverage corporate investment 
in impoverished areas. 

</P>
<P>
	Ill. Slay Suspect Killed Self  
</P>
<P>
	SALEM, Ill. (AP) -- A white supremacist who targeted minorities  
in a shooting spree that killed two and injured several in two 
states fatally shot himself after grappling with police, 
investigators said. Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 21, was being pursued 
Sunday after he carjacked a van in rural Marion County, Ill., said 
the FBI. Authorities believe Smith began his drive-by killing spree 
in Chicago on Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO-Russia Deal Is Reached  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Russia and NATO agreed today on how  
Moscow is to deploy more troops in Kosovo. The Russians will patrol 
in parts of the American, German and French sectors. NATO hopes the 
Russians will reassure Kosovo Serbs, who feel their fellow Slavs 
and traditional allies will protect them. Flights of Russian troops 
into Kosovo could begin as soon as tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton, Barak Speak by Telephone  
</P>
<P>
	HAZARD, Ky. (AP) -- President Clinton spoke briefly today with  
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak. Barak, scheduled to take 
office this week, is expected to visit Washington within a few 
weeks. The two leaders discussed the possibility of a visit, though 
no date was set. Barak has named his Cabinet and promised to bring 
the country peace and prosperity. 

</P>
<P>
	Dozens Hurt in La. Blasts  
</P>
<P>
	GRAMERCY, La. (AP) -- Explosions rocked an aluminum plant early  
today, spraying a red mist of corrosive chemical over residential 
areas and sending dozens of people to hospitals. The blasts at the 
Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical Co. shook houses and broke windows. 
Nineteen workers were treated in a hospital, with four taken to 
burn units. Another worker suffered eye injuries and one underwent 
surgery for cuts. 

</P>
<P>
	World Stocks Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks closed higher today, with oil,  
telecommunications and chemical companies leading the way. In Japan 
and Hong Kong, the main stock gauges rose to their highest levels 
in more than 20 months. Other markets in Asia closed generally 
higher. 

</P>
<P>
	'Wild Wild West' Tops Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Will Smith's ``Wild Wild West'' roped about  
$36.8 million in movie ticket sales over the Fourth of July holiday 
weekend. ``Big Daddy'' with Adam Sandler came in second at the 
weekend box office, while ``Tarzan'' was third. 

</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra Gets All-Star Nod  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra edged Derek Jeter for the  
starting American League spot at shortstop for next week's All-Star 
game. The AL voting was released today. Four members of the 
Cleveland Indians made the starting lineup: Jim Thome will be at 
first base and Roberto Alomar starts at second; Cleveland's Kenny 
Lofton and Manny Ramirez join leading vote-getter Ken Griffey Jr. 
of Seattle in the outfield. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals Beat Diamondbacks  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Cardinals' Jose Jimenez followed up  
his June 25 no-hitter against Arizona with a two-hitter in a 1-0 
victory today vs. the Diamondbacks. Jimenez (5-8) retired the first 
13 batters, before Steve Finley doubled with one out in the fifth. 
That was Arizona's first hit in 13 1-3 innings off Jimenez. The 
Diamondbacks' only other hit was a single off Jimenez's glove by 
Andy Fox to lead off the sixth. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
