<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 15:29:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Fireworks, Heat Mark East's Fourth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Thousands watched along the city's riverfront as  
splashes of stunning fireworks dotted the sky, capping a day of 
free concerts, foot races and enveloping summer heat throughout the 
East. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York crowd turned Manhattan's FDR Drive into a giant,  
paved viewing stage, dragging coolers and lawn chairs onto the 
normally bustling roadway to snag the show's best views. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 52 tons of fireworks exploded over the East River in  
celebration of the nation's 223rd birthday. ``It's exciting to come 
here to see the big fireworks,'' said an awed Rachel Laing, 10. 
</P>
<P>
	For much of the nation, there was something else that awed  
Independence Day revelers -- the heat. Parades, fireworks and 
backyard barbecues all came with a furnace-like dose of brow-wiping 
temperatures. 
</P>
<P>
	In humid Boston, a crowd of 500,000 watched Boston Symphony  
Orchestra Music Director Seiji Ozawa conduct Tchaikovsky's ``1812 
Overture'' while cannons boomed and fireworks lit the Charles 
River. 
</P>
<P>
	During a choral performance, U.S. Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,  
read words composed in 1963 by his late brother, President John F. 
Kennedy. ``Our most basic common link is that we inhabit this small 
planet,'' he told the cheering, jubilant crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	In Fort Dix, N.J., less than 500 ethnic Albanian refugees  
remained to celebrate their last weekend in a resettlement village. 
The village, designed for those who fled Kosovo, is scheduled to 
close within a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents were urged to stay cool in Philadelphia as the heat  
index rose to 110 degrees, the National Weather Service said. Early 
in the day, 112 people born on Independence Day since 1900 gathered 
for a ``Photo of the Century'' in front of Independence Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	Virginia roasted under record-breaking heat, with a new Fourth  
of July high of 97 degrees at Dulles International Airport. On the 
west lawn of Thomas Jefferson's Monticello in Charlottesville, 87 
people were sworn in during traditional naturalization ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have lived in the United States for 19 years and I took time  
to decide to be a U.S. citizen,'' said Carmen Aguilar, a native of 
Venezuela. ``This is the very best decision of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barbecuers also braved temperatures in the mid-90s in Michigan,  
where National Weather Service forecaster Fred Keyes found hope in 
cool front projected to arrive Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That could cool us -- cool, that's a relative word, isn't it? --  
into the 80s,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The South wasn't much cooler. In Atlanta, 82-degree heat  
blanketed paradegoers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we leave here without passing out, we're going to rest at  
home before going to see some fireworks,'' said Deborah Anderson as 
she watched festivities with her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	In Augusta, Ga., about 50 people saluted hundreds of tattered  
and faded old American flags before dousing them in kerosene and 
setting them ablaze, the method recommended for destroying old 
flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Beaches were packed from Maine to Miami. An estimated 200,000  
sun worshippers crammed into Los Angeles to bask atop the Southern 
California sand. 
</P>
<P>
	Festivities in the City of Angels also included a convention by  
Mensa, the national high-IQ group, and a music festival by L.A. 
Friends of Tibet, a group advocating liberation of the 
Chinese-occupied nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Someone who didn't get much time off this holiday weekend was  
Bill Ronayne, owner of West Brandywine Valley Heating &AMP; Air 
Conditioning of West Chester, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	``The phone's ringing off the hook,'' Ronayne said. Residents  
with ailing air conditioners, Ronayne said, ``want their cooling 
back on, and they want it now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still others decided to do the unthinkable: They went running.  
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of New Yorkers took part in a charity run through  
Central Park -- on a day where the city's heat index hit 111 
degrees. Barbecues and outdoor concerts followed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have air conditioning in my apartment, so this is just  
as good,'' said Shirley Hawn, 40, of Manhattan, while she sat in a 
folding chair fanning herself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0151 </DOCNO>
