<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore OKs Home Tech Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- Singapore has changed its regulations to allow  
high-tech entrepreneurs to set up businesses in their homes, the 
government announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is part of Singapore's ``technopreneurship'' drive to  
make the city-state an information technology hotbed like Silicon 
Valley in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``These home offices could be the equivalent of home garages in  
the United States that have spawned many high-tech enterprises, 
like Apple Computer,'' the government said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of Singapore's 3.2 million people live in high-rise public  
housing blocks, which previously were subject to strict bans on 
commercial use. 
</P>
<P>
	Would-be entrepreneurs now may apply to the National Science and  
Technology Board for permission to set up companies in their homes, 
the board said in the statement, which was issued jointly with the 
Urban Redevelopment Authority and the Housing and Development 
Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The businesses' main activity should be related to information  
technology, integrated circuit design, Internet software or a 
similar field, the officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore earlier this year announced plans to set up a $1  
billion venture capital fund to boost high-tech development. 
</P>
<P>
	The wealthy island republic is Southeast Asia's most highly  
developed country and enjoys one of the world's highest standards 
of living. The government has recently been pushing computer 
technology and electronic commerce as ways to make the country more 
competitive. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
