<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	East Swelters in Hot, Muggy Weather  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Record heat and sticky, humid air enveloped the  
eastern third of the nation today. Temperature records started 
falling a few minutes after noon, with Portland, Maine, reaching 
94. Raleigh-Durham, N.C., hit 102. New York City and Atlantic City, 
N.J., rose to a record 101. In separate holiday weekend incidents, 
two young children -- one in Omaha, Neb., another in Masontown, Pa. 
-- died of heat exposure. 

</P>
<P>
	Ecuador Taxi Strike Causes Emergency  
</P>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador declared a state of emergency  
today after striking taxi drivers blocked traffic in major cities 
to protest gas price increases. Police detained 43 drivers who had 
formed blockades in the cities of Quito and Guayaquil, snarling 
traffic and forcing thousands of people to wait for the few buses 
that circulated. The strike comes as this poor South American 
nation of 12 million people faces its worst economic crisis in 
decades. 

</P>
<P>
	Suicide Bomber Injures 17 in Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	ADANA, Turkey (AP) -- A 19-year-old Kurdish woman flashed the  
``V'' for victory sign today before detonating bombs strapped to 
her body outside a Turkish police station, killing herself and 
injuring 17 people. It was the third major attack blamed on Kurdish 
guerrillas since a Turkish court sentenced Kurdish rebel leader 
Abdullah Ocalan to death June 29 for treason and separatism. The 
assailant was identified as Rusen Tabanci. The Anatolia news agency 
said she was a Kurdish rebel wanted by security forces. 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Pushes Northern Ireland Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- British Prime Minister Tony  
Blair appealed to Northern Ireland's major Protestant party today 
to back his plan to rescue the troubled peace accord and accept 
Sinn Fein as government partners. Amid rising political tensions, a 
Protestant mob clashed with police in the main Catholic district of 
Portadown early Tuesday. There were no immediate reports of serious 
injury. 

</P>
<P>
	Minn. Boat Crash Death Toll at Five  
</P>
<P>
	BAYPORT, Minn. (AP) -- The death toll from a weekend boating  
accident rose to five as divers pulled two more bodies from the 
murky St. Croix River. The bodies were those of two 26-year-old 
men. The three other confirmed victims, all men in their early 30s, 
were found on Saturday and Sunday. The two pleasure boats 
apparently were traveling in approximately the same direction 
toward Hudson, Wis., when they collided shortly after 1 a.m. on 
Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	Motive Sought in Shooting Spree  
</P>
<P>
	SALEM, Ill. (AP) -- Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 21, targeted  
minorities in an shooting spree that killed two and injured at 
least eight others before killing himself, investigators said. But 
authorities and acquaintances wondered Monday what would drive a 
rich kid -- described as hateful but publicly reserved and even 
``very polite'' -- to go on such a two-state shooting attack. 

</P>
<P>
	Hopes High for Cystic Fibrosis Drug  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Studies of three drugs called ``gene assist  
therapies'' are in the early stages of an experiment to see if they 
will attack the cause of deadly cystic fibrosis rather than just 
treat its symptoms. If they work, patients could expect more normal 
lives by using a daily medicine to control the genetic defect that 
causes cystic fibrosis, which attacks patients' lungs with a thick 
mucus. 

</P>
<P>
	'Wild Wild West' Tops Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Will Smith's ``Wild Wild West'' roped in  
about $36.8 million in movie ticket sales over the Fourth of July 
holiday weekend. ``Big Daddy'' with Adam Sandler came in second at 
the weekend box office, while ``Tarzan'' was third. The ``South 
Park'' feature opened to a respectable $14.8 million in fourth 
despite tougher enforcement of the R rating, which limited the 
audience. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell moderately on Tuesday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average shed 94.89 points to 18,040.17 in early 
trading. Financial markets in New York were closed for the 
Independence Day holiday. 

</P>
<P>
	Mets Beat Expos 2-1  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On the hottest day of the season, Brian McRae  
pushed home the go-ahead run with a double-play grounder in the 
eighth inning, and the New York Mets beat Montreal 2-1. New York, 
which has come from behind in seven of its last nine victories, is 
still struggling at the plate. Still, the Mets have won 20 of their 
last 28, including 10 of 13 at home. Montreal has lost four 
straight and nine of 12. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
