<DOCNO> APW19990705.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 04:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Stars Emerge at Wimbeldon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Wimbledon had all its usual traditions  
-- rained out days, long lines of people waiting for tickets, Pete 
Sampras winning again. 
</P>
<P>
	And the stately All England Club this year also showcased  
another new group of young talented women. 
</P>
<P>
	Two qualifiers -- 18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson and 16-year-old  
Jelena Dokic -- emerged from virtual obscurity to make their mark 
and reach the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson, amid a storm of publicity about the identity of her  
father and her mother's allegations of racism and lesbianism, got 
to the semis by beating Dokic, who had stunned everyone by ousting 
No. 1 Marina Hingis in the opening round. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson, whose father is basketball great Julius Erving,  
crumbled 6-1, 6-1 in the semis to the eventual titlist, Lindsay 
Davenport. But the 6-foot-1 American showed she has the power game 
to be a major force on the women's tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirjana Lucic, a 17-year-old from Croatia, also made it to the  
semis, but lost to Steffi Graf after taking the first set. Now 
living in Florida, Lucic has escaped from a stormy relationship 
with her father and has recaptured the amazing form she showed in 
1997 when she won her first tournament after turning pro. 
</P>
<P>
	Venus Williams, now 19, underlined her own potential by ousting  
Anna Kournikova and gaining the quarters, only to lose to Graf in 
probably the highest quality match of the women's championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Hingis went out in the first round, Wimbledons of the  
near future could very likely be dominated by the young Swiss star, 
Davenport, Williams, Stevenson, Dokic, Lucic and maybe Kournikova. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrival of the newcomers coincided with the departure of two  
old favorites. 
</P>
<P>
	Boris Becker had already announced it would be his last  
Wimbledon, but he didn't go quietly. The three-time titlist, who 
last won in 1989 and is now playing on a part-time basis, powered 
through three rounds before losing to second-seeded Rat Rafter to 
take one more final standing ovation, including from the Royal Box. 
</P>
<P>
	Graf's departure was a little less grand, mainly because she  
only announced it after she had lost 6-4, 7-5 in the women's final 
to Lindsay Davenport. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old German, who had won seven titles and came here  
on the back of a French Open triumph a month ago, said she wouldn't 
be returning. She said that at Roland Garros, too, and organizers 
of the U.S. Open, which takes place in late August-early September, 
are awaiting further word from a player who has won 22 Grand Slam 
singles titles and is two short of Margaret Court's record. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Becker and Graf next year, Wimbledon certainly will seem  
different. 
</P>
<P>
	But, while the women's title seemingly has several leading  
contenders, who is strong enough to take the men's championship 
from Sampras? 
</P>
<P>
	By beating Agassi on Sunday, the 27-year-old Californian has won  
six titles in seven years, and his latest performance was probably 
his best. 
</P>
<P>
	If Sampras, especially on grass, is getting better, what chance  
do his rivals have? 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Henman, rated by Sampras as a future Wimbledon champion,  
took the first set off the defending titlist, but his game deflated 
under the pressure of the big-serving world No. 1 and he lost to 
the American in the semifinal for the second year in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Philippoussis also took the first set against Sampras in  
the quarters but was forced to withdraw with a knee injury early in 
the second, so his chances of beating the American can't be judged. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Rafter, the second-seeded Australian, was outplayed by  
Agassi in the semifinal and didn't get to face Sampras. 
</P>
<P>
	However much they all fancy their chances, Sampras shows no sign  
of giving up his title and certainly has no plans to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``The game to me right now is to do well at the majors,'' he  
said. ``Grand Slams are so much more at stake than being No. 1, and 
I feel I've done that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Grand Slams are always going to be playing this game in my  
early to mid-30s, whenever I call it a day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 17:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect in Shooting Spree Kills Self </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALEM, Ill. (AP) -- A white supremacist suspected of targeting  
minorities in a deadly two-state drive-by shooting spree committed 
suicide by shooting himself three times as officers pursued him. 
</P>
<P>
	Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 21, led officers on a slow-speed  
pursuit late Sunday after he ditched his blue Ford Taurus and 
carjacked a minivan at gunpoint at a gas station in the southern 
Illinois town of Ina, Marion County Sheriff Gerald L. Benjamin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman who was driving the minivan and her 13-year-old  
daughter escaped without injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after entering Salem, about 35 miles north of Ina, Smith  
shot himself under the chin. The minivan then went off the left 
side of the road and hit a small, abandoned building, causing the 
air bag to inflate. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith refused officers' orders to put his hands up, so several  
entered the van. As he struggled with five sheriff's deputies and 
police officers who tried to subdue him, Smith shot himself in the 
chest and leg. None of the officers fired and Smith didn't appear 
to shoot at them, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was still combative even after being handcuffed and put in an  
ambulance but said nothing, police said. He bled to death from the 
chest wound a short time later in a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad it's over,'' Benjamin said. ``I feel sorry for his  
parents and the victims and their relatives. I don't know what 
caused this but it's very sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith had been heading toward a crowd of about 2,000 people  
gathered two miles down the road for Independence Day festivities. 
``Our main target was to get him stopped before he got there, but 
fortunately he did that for us,'' Deputy Todd Garden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people were killed during the drive-by spree, including  
former Northwestern University men's basketball coach Ricky 
Byrdsong, who was black, and a Korean student in Bloomington, Ind. 
At least eight others were wounded, one seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said they believed Smith began his drive-by killing  
spree in Chicago on Friday by wounding six Orthodox Jews leaving 
synagogue. Within an hour, Byrdsong was shot to death in nearby 
Skokie and two Asian-Americans were shot at, but not hit, while 
driving in Northbrook. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooter also fired at Asians and blacks in two Illinois  
cities on Saturday, seriously wounding one man, before the 
Bloomington shooting on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities also believe the gunman also wounded a black  
minister in Decatur, Ill., on Saturday, but they were waiting for 
ballistics tests to confirm that. 
</P>
<P>
	A .22-caliber handgun and a .380-caliber handgun found with  
Smith were consistent with the guns used in the shootings. 
Authorities were trying to trace the source of the weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was a member of the World Church of the Creator, a  
white-supremacist organization, and distributed anti-minority and 
anti-Semitic literature while a student at Indiana University in 
Bloomington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
