<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Steels Wins Tour de France Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAINT-NAZAIRE, France (AP) -- Ocean crossings can be treacherous.  
</P>
<P>
	Just ask a few top riders at the Tour de France, who stayed too  
far behind the pack during Monday's second stage and lost precious 
minutes when they got caught behind a crash on a narrow ocean 
causeway. 
</P>
<P>
	Tour officials no doubt included the Passage du Gois, which  
connects a small island to the mainland in the coastal Atlantic 
Vendee region, on the itinerary because it is quaint and 
picturesque. 
</P>
<P>
	But the causeway, which is submerged by water at high tide and  
only open part of the day, didn't seem so quaint for Alex Zulle, 
Michael Boogerd and Ivan Gotti, who never caught up to a group of 
50 or so riders that broke away from the pack after the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	It also wasn't friendly to American Jonathan Vaughters of the  
U.S. Postal Service team, who fractured his chin in the crash and 
had to retire from the race. Marc Wauters also abandoned with 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The stage was won in a final sprint by Tom Steels of Belgium,  
and the second-place finisher was Jaan Kirsipuu of Estonia, who 
took over the yellow jersey from Lance Armstrong because of bonus 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong remained in second place overall, and in excellent  
position to come on strong in the areas where he excels: a time 
trial on Sunday, and the later mountain climbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to stay out of trouble until the real race begins  
on Sunday with the time trial,'' Armstrong said. 
</P>
<P>
	In third and fourth place were sprinter Mario Cipollini of Italy  
and Germany's Erik Zabel. 
</P>
<P>
	The pivotal crash at the Passage du Gois wasn't even the first  
of the day; an earlier mishap at 21 miles involved 30 riders. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of vacationers lined the roads all through the  
109-mile stage, which came at the beginning of many French people's 
summer holiday. Many set up folding chairs and elaborate picnic 
tables along the road, or leaned out of balconies in small villages 
to join in the action. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with the occasional anti-doping banner -- ``Say No to EPO''  
-- many fans showed support for French cycling star Richard 
Virenque, under formal investigation for doping during last year's 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Allez Richard -- We Forgive You,'' said one banner held by two  
young children. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, a two-time Olympic cyclist, is now a favorite. The  
Texan won the 1993 World Championship and competed for the U.S. 
Olympic team in 1992 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1996, he was diagnosed with testicular cancer that  
had spread to his lungs and brain. He underwent surgery to remove 
his right testicle and lesions from his brain, and returned to 
racing early last year. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Monday that he thought the doping scandal was  
``exaggerated and overblown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to think that nobody here has anything to hide,'' he  
said in an interview, complaining of over-aggressive tactics during 
last year's drug busts by French police. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 13:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steels Wins Tour de France Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAINT-NAZAIRE, France (AP) -- With some top riders caught behind  
a crash on an ocean causeway, Tom Steels of Belgium won the second 
stage of the Tour de France on Monday and Lance Armstrong of Texas 
lost the overall lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Another American, Jonathan Vaughters, fractured his chin in the  
crash and had to retire from cycling's showcase race. Estonia's 
Jaan Kirsipuu was second in Monday's stage and took the leader's 
yellow jersey from Armstrong. 
</P>
<P>
	The spill happened on the Passage du Gois, which connects a  
small island to the mainland in the coastal Atlantic Vendee region. 
The strip of land is no more than two car lengths wide and is 
closed during high tide. 
</P>
<P>
	The road proved treacherous for such favorites as Alex Zulle,  
Michael Boogerd and Ivan Gotti. They lost valuable minutes when 
they were behind the 10-rider crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughters and Armstrong both ride for the U.S. Postal Service  
team. Armstrong, recovering from testicular cancer, is second 
overall. He is in excellent position for Sunday's time trial and 
the later mountain climbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to stay out of trouble until the real race begins  
on Sunday with the time trial,'' Armstrong said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirsipuu earned bonus points in winning two of the day's three  
sprints. In third and fourth place were sprinter Mario Cipollini of 
Italy and Germany's Erik Zabel. 
</P>
<P>
	In another strong showing for U.S. Postal, George Hincapie came  
in sixth and is seventh overall. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughters was taken to a hospital in Nantes, as was Marc  
Wauters, who also is out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash wasn't the first of the day -- there was an earlier  
mishap at 21 miles involving 30 riders. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of vacationers lined the roads through the 109-mile  
stage, which came at the beginning of the summer holiday for many 
of the French. 
</P>
<P>
	Vacationers set up folding chairs and elaborate picnic tables  
along the road and leaned out of balconies in small villages. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with the occasional anti-drug banner -- ``Say No to EPO'' --  
many fans showed support for French cycling star Richard Virenque. 
He is under investigation for last year's race that was nearly cut 
short because of the drug scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Allez Richard -- We Forgive You,'' said one banner held by two  
young children. 
</P>
<P>
	Race organizers say there will be spot drug tests during the  
coming days. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong won the world championship in 1993 and competed in the  
Olympics in 1992 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1996, he was diagnosed with testicular cancer that  
had spread to his lungs and brain. He had surgery to remove his 
right testicle and brain lesions, and returned to racing early last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Monday he thought the drug scandal was ``exaggerated and  
overblown.'' He also complained of what he said were aggressive 
tactics during last year's drug busts by French police. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to think that nobody here has anything to hide,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 23:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
