<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Shipping Companies Plan Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- Dutch storage, distribution and  
shipping companies Royal Pakhoed NV and Royal Van Ommeren NV on 
Monday announced they plan to merge. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies, which had combined sales of 3.3 billion euros  
($3.2 billion) in 1988, tried but failed to join forces last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger, which will create a new company to be named Vopak,  
is expected to be completed by the end of October, the companies 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Vopak will focus on combining storage, distribution and shipping  
activities into integrated services for the chemicals, oil and gas 
industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakhoed and Van Ommeren said they expect the merger to result in  
cost-cutting but did not give details. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakhoed will have a 63.4 percent stake in the new company, while  
Van Ommeren will hold the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said corporate offices will be combined in a new  
headquarters in Rotterdam, leading to an unspecified number of job 
losses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
