<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate a Haven for Senior Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Ernest Hollings, 77, last year handily  
defeated a challenger exactly half his age to extend his record of 
being a junior senator longer than any man in history. 
</P>
<P>
	The South Carolina Democrat has been in the Senate for 33 years,  
going back to the Johnson administration. Still, he is far 
outranked by his 96-year-old Republican colleague Strom Thurmond, 
who entered the Senate in 1954. 
</P>
<P>
	In a nation that puts a premium on youth, the Senate remains a  
bastion of senior power. Including Thurmond and Hollings, 13 of the 
100 members are older than 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them are Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., 81; William Roth, R-Del.,  
77; Jesse Helms, R-N.C., 77; and John Chafee, R.I., 76. Both of 
Hawaii's senators, Democrats Daniel Inouye and Daniel Akaka, are 
74. 
</P>
<P>
	Even seniority must bow to political control. In the years when  
the Democrats were the majority party, Hollings was chairman of the 
Senate Commerce Committee and wielded more power than Thurmond. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, 75, who entered the Senate in 1968,  
recently celebrated his 12,000th vote, still well behind Senate 
record-holder Byrd, who has cast his ayes and nays more than 15,000 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	The word Senate derives from the Latin for counsel of elders,  
said Senate historian Donald Ritchie, and particularly in the 20th 
century, with the advent of direct elections and the entrenchment 
of the seniority system, it is not uncommon for senators to serve 
well into their senior years. 
</P>
<P>
	Theodore Green of Rhode Island was 93 when he retired in 1960,  
the record before Thurmond, and John Stennis of Mississippi retired 
in 1988 at age 87. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike House members who have to run for re-election every two  
years, senators have six years to sink political roots in their 
states, making them extremely difficult to unseat, said Notre Dame 
professor Robert Schmuhl, who studies Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are able to toss their weight around over that longer  
period of time to the benefit of people in their state,'' he said. 
Also, ``senators of a certain age have a strong appeal to those who 
are roughly their own age,'' other seniors who turn out at the 
polls in higher percentages than other age groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The average age of the Senate actually dipped slightly after the  
1998 elections, to 58, with the election of such youngsters as 
Blanche Lincoln, D-Ark., and Peter Fitzgerald, R-Ill., now both 38. 
The average age in the House is 52. 
</P>
<P>
	But gray power dominates where it counts, among the committee  
chairmen. The average chairman's age is 67, even though Thurmond, 
in a nod to youth, this year ceded his seat as Armed Services 
Committee chairman to Sen. John Warner, R-Va., who is 72. 
</P>
<P>
	The terms of seven of the plus-70 crowd are up next year, and  
four have indicated they will run for re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I've got a pain in my body I don't know about it,'' Byrd  
said in a recent interview with The Intelligencer of Wheeling, 
W.Va. ``Why would I quit? If it's God's will and West Virginia's 
will, then I'll be re-elected,'' he said of his decision to seek an 
eighth term. 
</P>
<P>
	Roth, chairman of the Finance Committee, would be 79 at the  
beginning of his sixth term in 2001. He said Delaware voters should 
consider ``the experience, the seniority and, yes, the power that 
we have earned together.'' Both he and Byrd are shoo-ins for 
re-election. 
</P>
<P>
	Hawaii's Akaka and Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., 71, are also  
expected to run again. Three others -- Chafee, 75-year-old Frank 
Lautenberg, D-N.J., and 72-year-old Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. 
-- are retiring at the end of their terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're in your 70s and you don't want to press that too long,  
do you?'' the four-term Moynihan said in announcing his decision to 
step down. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sentiments were echoed in 1997 when former Sen. John  
Glenn, D-Ohio, then 75, revealed that he would not seek a fifth 
term. ``There is still no cure for the common birthday,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a year later, at age 77, America's first man to orbit  
the Earth rocketed back into space aboard the space shuttle as the 
world's oldest astronaut. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
