<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Hoskins Surprised by Noriega </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bob Hoskins, who plays Manuel Noriega in an  
upcoming cable TV movie, found the former Panamanian dictator more 
layered than he expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before I read the script, my impression of Noriega was the  
same as everyone else's -- that he was a monster, a trumped-up 
little dictator,'' Hoskins told the Los Angeles Times on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a lot more complex and interesting than that,'' he said.  
``But it's not my job to make a judgment whether the guy is good or 
evil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 56-year-old British actor stars in ``Noriega: God's  
Favorite,'' scheduled to be shown later this year on Showtime. He 
and other cast members are working for modest salaries on the $5 
million project, which is being filmed in the Philippines. 
</P>
<P>
	Noriega's dictatorship was toppled when the United States  
invaded Panama in 1989. He continues to serve time in Miami on 1992 
federal money laundering and drug trafficking convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge recently reduced his sentence, possibly making Noriega,  
65, eligible for release by 2007. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
