<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 13:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Jet Mark Gastineau Is Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former New York Jets defensive end Mark  
Gastineau was arrested Monday for violating an order of protection 
in an ongoing domestic dispute, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gastineau, 42, surrendered at a Queens precinct stationhouse and  
remained in custody awaiting arraignment on a charge of criminal 
contempt. 
</P>
<P>
	The ex-NFL star allegedly violated a court order on June 22 by  
going to his wife's Queens home, where he repeatedly rang the 
doorbell and refused to leave, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gastineau was sentenced last October to three months probation  
after pleading guilty to a misdemeanor assault charge for hitting 
his wife. He had been arrested a month earlier for hitting his 
then-fiancee, Patricia Schorr, at a Manhattan apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	Gastineau was charged with misdemeanor assault, menacing and  
criminal possession of a weapon. The court complaint said the 
weapon was a glass cocktail table with which he threatened to hit 
Schorr. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of Gastineau's guilty plea, Schorr said she had  
married him in late September. She also refused to cooperate in the 
prosecution of her husband. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 14:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Thrives at University Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- Olympic hopeful Mark  
Warkentin picked up two more golds Monday and cracked the 
University Games record for the men's 800-meter freestyle by nearly 
four seconds, leading the U.S. swimming team to victories in five 
of the day's six events. 
</P>
<P>
	But Olympic champion Anita Nall finished fourth and out of the  
medals in the women's 200 breaststroke, the event in which she 
shattered the world record twice in one day at the 1992 U.S. 
Olympic trials. It was her first taste of international competition 
since the 1995 Pan-American Games, because she has suffered blood 
pressure problems. 
</P>
<P>
	She won a gold, silver and bronze at the 1992 Summer Games in  
Barcelona. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like forever ago,'' Nall said of her Olympic  
triumphs. ``I would have liked to have gone a little faster today, 
and been in the top three. But I'm not disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her time of 2:33.00 was more than four seconds off her 1992  
world record and a second behind winner Yuko Sakaguchi of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Warkentin cut about six seconds off his personal best time,  
winning the 800 free in 8 minutes, 0.81 seconds. He held off 
Italy's late-charging Andrea Righi and eclipsed the mark of 8:04.80 
set by Canada's Thurlough O'Hare at the 1993 University Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninety minutes later, he anchored the U.S. team to victory in  
the 4x200 freestyle relay in 7:27.33. Ukraine was second in 
7:28.49. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking the 200 free as a late fill-in on Sunday, Warkentin  
is shooting at five golds here. He'll race the 400 free, his best 
event, on Wednesday, and the 1,500 free on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ask some of the coaches I've been around and they'll tell you  
this meet was a long time due,'' Warkentin said. ``I have been 
waiting for big drops in my time and I knew it was going to come. 
It was just a matter of what meet and it happened to come here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Somensatto (200 butterfly), Beau Wiebel (400 individual  
medley) and Kimberly Black (200 freestyle) won the other U.S. golds 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women opened defense of their 1997 basketball gold  
medal by beating China 107-89, despite losing point guard Brandi 
McCain, who strained her right knee driving to the basket with one 
second left in the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina's LaQuanda Barksdale led six Americans in double  
figures with 15 points. China's Lijie Miao led all scorers with 24. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men's team improved to 3-0 here, and stretched its  
University Games winning streak to 35 games overall, by thrashing 
the Czech Republic 102-43. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, world champion Svetlana Khornika posted the top  
scores in three of four events to win the women's gymnastics 
all-around title, while Ukraine's Alexander Beresh won the men's 
all-around gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Americans pulled out with injuries. Heather Renee Brink was  
taken to the hospital for X-rays after suffering what appeared to 
be a broken foot during the floor exercise, her second discipline. 
Mohini Bhardwaj withdrew before action started Monday because she 
aggravated an elbow injury in the team competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining American, UCLA's Heidi Louise Moneymaker, finished  
16th of 24 women. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990705.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-05 11:55:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Iran Museum Houses Hitler Paintings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- A Tehran museum holds two  
watercolor paintings by Adolf Hitler, given decades ago by the 
Fuhrer himself to the Iranian ambassador to Germany, the museum's 
curator said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohammad Reza Javaheri said the paintings show scenes of the  
Austrian capital of Vienna, where the 18-year-old Hitler applied to 
study art, but was rejected. The paintings are owned by the 
government foundation Bonyad Mostazafan, which runs the museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both paintings have been authenticated by two European  
experts,'' the official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted 
Javaheri as saying. The works have never been appraised, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The foundation does not intend to sell the paintings. They  
will remain in its collection,'' he said, according to the 
Dubai-monitored broadcast. 
</P>
<P>
	The paintings, both watercolors on paper, measure 23 1/2 inches by  
nearly 20 inches and show two mansion-like monuments of Vienna, 
sources told the Associated Press by telephone from Tehran, 
speaking on the customary condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitler presented the paintings to Hassan Esfandiari, the Iranian  
ambassador to Germany during Hitler's rule, Javaheri said. Iran was 
sympathetic toward Germany during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bonyad Mostazafan gained the paintings after the 1979  
Islamic revolution, when the clerical government seized billions of 
dollars in assets owned by the ousted shah and his cronies and gave 
them to the newly created foundation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
